sister news channels which provide coverage in Hindi, English and several regional languages of India. Zee News was launched on 27 August 1999 as Zee Sports Ltd. The company was [[Certificate of incorporation|reincorporated]] on 27 May 2004 as Zee News Ltd.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/company/zee-media-27705/information/company-history|title=Zee Media Corporation Ltd.|date=|work=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, Zee News Ltd changed its name to Zee Media Corporation Limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/zee-media-corporation-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-18879.cms|title=Zee Media Corporation History {{!}} Zee Media Corporation Information|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Economic Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The Zee News channel is the flagship channel of the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/stock/zee-media-corporation-ltd_zeenews/reports-directors-report|title=Director Reports, Company Results of Zee Media Corp|last=|first=|date=|website=[[NDTV Profit]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe chairman of the group is [[Subhash Chandra]], who is a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]-backed member of the [[Rajya Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohan|first=Archis|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/politics/subhash-chandra-bets-on-bjp-support-for-rajya-sabha-entry-116053101457_1.html|title=Subhash Chandra bets on BJP support for Rajya Sabha entry|date=2016-06-01|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] is the editor-in-chief of Zee News and the anchor of the prime time show on the channel.<ref name=\"exch1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exchange4media.mobi/tv/sudhir-chaudhary-now-also-editor-in-chief-of-zee-business_68276.html|title=Sudhir Chaudhary now also editor in Chief of zee business|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170715163422/http://www.exchange4media.mobi/tv/sudhir-chaudhary-now-also-editor-in-chief-of-zee-business_68276.html|archive-date=15 July 2017|access-date=15 July 2017|df=}}</ref> The channel has been involved in several controversies and has broadcast fabricated news stories on multiple occasions.<ref name=\"fake\">List of sources:\n\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/book-extract/book-extract-republic-tv-age-of-fake-news-and-promoters-in-indian-tv-newsrooms|title=Book extract: Republic TV, age of fake news and promoters in Indian TV newsrooms|last=Bhushan|first=Sandeep|date=2019-06-29|website=[[National Herald (India)|National Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/read/the-troubling-association-of-zee-and-jlf/article30693362.ece|title=The festival and its funder|last=Jha|first=Aditya Mani|date=2020-01-31|website=[[Business Line]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/zee-news-broadcasts-old-unrelated-satellite-visuals-as-destroyed-jem-camp-in-balakot/|title=Zee News broadcasts old, unrelated satellite visuals as destroyed JEM camp in Balakot|last=Patel|first=Jignesh|date=2019-03-08|website=[[Alt News]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/zee-news-producer-quits-video-we-shot-had-no-pakistan-zindabad-slogan/|title=Zee News producer quits: Video we shot had no Pakistan Zindabad slogan|last=Hafeez|first=Sarah|date=2018-02-22|website=[[The Indian Express]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/india-news-are-newsrooms-run-by-political-masters-why-are-editors-compromising-on-truth-telling/302846|title=Are Newsrooms Run By Political Masters? Why Are Editors Compromising On Truth Telling?|last=Yadav|first=Puneet|date=2020-02-21|website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/hoaxposed/zee-news-tweets-doctored-video-of-navjot-sidhus-rajasthan-rally/158011/|title=Zee News tweets doctored video of Navjot Sidhu\u2019s Rajasthan rally|last=Rampal|first=Nikhil|date=2018-12-03|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.catchnews.com/politics-news/saffron-journalism-zee-news-and-art-of-manufacturing-anti-nationals-1457687402.html|title=Saffron journalism: Zee News & art of manufacturing anti-nationals|last=Menon|first=Aditya|date=10 February 2017|website=catchnews.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/politics/zee-news-subhash-chandra-sudhir-chaudhary-narendra-modi-bhakt-sangh-jnu-bjp-muslims-pakistan-anupam-kher/story/1/9474.html|title=Subhash Chandra failed to convince Zee is not Modi's mouthpiece|last=Khan|first=Saif Ahmed|date=2016-03-10|website=[[India Today|DailyO]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The channel is subjected to an ongoing criminal defamation case against legislator [[Mahua Moitra]] as of March 2020.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Outlets ==\n\n=== Television ===\nThe Zee Media Corporation Limited (ZMCL) operates a number of other channels, some in regional languages with the stated intent of providing a pan-Indian reach.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-profile/ZEEN.BO|title=Profile: Zee Media Corporation Ltd (ZEEN.BO)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Reuters]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/zee-media-to-foray-into-english-news-broadcasting-1512583.html|title=Zee Media to foray into English news broadcasting|last=|first=|date=17 August 2015|website=[[Moneycontrol]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zeemedia.in/channeloverview.html|title=ZMCL Channels Overview|last=|first=|date=|website=www.zeemedia.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''World is One News (WION):''' [[English language]] news channel.\n* '''Zee Business:''' Hindi language business news channel.\n*'''Zee Hindustan:''' 24/7 national Hindi language news channel. It was relaunched in 2017 as an anchor-less news channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/media-tv-news/zee-hindustan-re-launched-as-anchor-less-channel-93472.html|title=Zee Hindustan re-launched as anchor-less channel - Exchange4media|last=|first=|date=|website=exchange4media.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> It was formerly branded as Zee Sangam and India 24x7.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://bestmediainfo.com/2017/05/india-24x7-is-now-zee-hindustan/|title=India 24x7 is now Zee Hindustan|last=|first=|last2=|date=23 May 2017|website=Best Media Info|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=}}</ref>\n* '''Zee 24 Taas:''' 24/7 [[Marathi language]] regional news channel.\n*'''Zee 24 Kalak:''' 24/7 [[Gujarati language]] regional news channel. It was inaugurated on 20 August 2017 by [[Vijay Rupani]], the [[Chief minister (India)|Chief Minister]] of Gujarat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-gujarat-cm-deputy-cm-launch-new-dna-ahmedabad-and-zee-24-kalak-2542970|title=Gujarat CM, Deputy CM launch new DNA Ahmedabad and Zee 24 Kalak|last=|first=|date=2017-09-04|website=[[Zee News|DNA India]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n*'''Zee Rajasthan:''' Hindi language news channel operating in Rajasthan. It was formerly branded as Zee Marudhara.\n*'''Zee Odisha:''' [[Odia language]] regional news channel. It was formerly branded as Zee Kalinga.\n*'''Zee Salaam:''' [[Urdu]] language news channel.\n*'''Zee Madhya Pradesh Chhattisgarh:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Chhattisgarh]].\n*'''Zee Punjab Haryana Himachal:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Haryana]] and [[Himachal Pradesh]].\n*'''Zee Bihar Jharkhand:''' Hindi and [[Bhojpuri language]] news channel operating in Bihar and Jharkhand. It was known as Maurya TV and Zee Purvaiya before the current branding.\n*'''Zee Uttar Pradesh Uttarakhand:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Uttarakhand]].\n\nThe company also runs two regional news channels through its subsidiaries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* '''Zee 24 Ghanta:''' 24/7 [[Bengali language]] regional news channel. It is owned by the Zee Akash News Pvt Ltd subsidiary.\n\n[[File:DailyNewsandAnalysisCover.jpg|thumb|Cover of ''Daily News & Analysis''.]]\n\n=== Online ===\nZee News operates the Daily News & Analysis and Zee News websites to provide online coverage of the channel. The Zee5 Website which is owned by the [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises]] is used to platform coverage of other ZMCL channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esselgroup.com/zee-media-corporation-limited.html|title=Zee Media Corporation Limited|last=|first=|date=|website=esselgroup.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The World is One News (WION) channel operates its own WION website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/08/18/zee-english-news-channel_n_8002024.html|title=Zee Group To Launch English News Channel, Hires Rohit Gandhi As Editor-In-Chief|last=Basu|first=Indrani|date=2015-08-18|website=[[Huffington Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The ZMCL also owns the India.com news website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/cautious-road-ahead-for-zee-entertainment/1787546/|title=Cautious road ahead for Zee Entertainment|last=|first=|date=2019-12-08|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''Zee News Website:''' English and Hindi language online news coverage service of Zee News.\n* '''Daily News & Analysis Website:''' English language online news coverage service. It is branded under the DNA program of Zee News.\n* '''Zee5 Website:''' Streaming service which hosts ZMCL news channels. \n*'''WION Website:''' English language online news coverage service of World is One News.\n*'''India.com:''' English and Hindi language news website owned by ZMCL.\n\n=== Newspaper ===\nThe Daily News & Analysis was an English-language [[broadsheet]] newspaper owned by the Zee Media Corporation Limited. It was launched in 2005 and branded under the Daily News & Analysis (DNA) program of Zee News. It was primarily circulated in [[Mumbai]] and discontinued on 9 October 2019 citing losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/dna-goes-out-of-print-14-years-after-launch-rise-fall-promising-newspaper/304050/|title=DNA goes out of print 14 years after launch \u2014 rise & sudden fall of a promising newspaper|last=Dutta|first=Amrita Nayak|date=2019-10-11|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronosphere.biz/IMO/26/imo.html#dna|title=DNA commissions E&Y to certify circulation|author=Bhupesh Trivedi|date=1 June 2006|work=Indian Media Observer (issue #26)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071219110303/http://www.chronosphere.biz/IMO/26/imo.html#dna|archivedate=19 December 2007|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Jindal Group incident ===\nThe channel was tried for allegedly extorting \u20b9100 [[Crore]] from the [[Jindal Group]] revealed through a sting operation.<ref name=\"The Hindu2\">{{cite news|last=Jebaraj|first=Priscilla|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/jindal-plays-cd-claims-zee-editors-demanded-rs-100-crore/article4031340.ece|title=Jindal plays CD, claims Zee editors demanded Rs. 100 crore|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=4 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Two senior journalists [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] and Sameer Ahluwalia were arrested.<ref name=\"NDTV India2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/naveen-jindal-vs-zee-senior-journalists-arrested-over-alleged-extortion-298095|title=Naveen Jindal vs Zee: Senior journalists arrested over alleged extortion|accessdate=4 December 2014|publisher=NDTV India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/Two-Zee-editors-arrested-for-Rs-100-crore-extortion-bid/articleshow/17391903.cms|title=Two Zee editors arrested for 'Rs 100-crore extortion bid' - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"The Australian2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/jindal-group-and-zee-television-in-extortion-scandal/story-e6frg6so-1226527713986?nk=e835e32ddf2956600de185626015a1b1|title=Jindal Group and Zee television in extortion scandal|accessdate=4 December 2014|publisher=The Australian}}</ref> [[Naveen Jindal]] had accused the two journalists of trying to extort  {{INRConvert|1,000,000,000||lk=on|year=2011}} in advertisements for Zee News from him through blackmail by threatening to air stories against his company in the [[Coalgate scam]]. Zee News denied the charges and made counter claims of Jindal offering them {{INRConvert|200000000||lk=on|year=2011}}  to halt their investigations against [[Jindal Steel]]'s involvement in the scam but filed no charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Naveen-Jindal-accuses-Zee-News-of-extortion-channel-hits-back/articleshow/16956098.cms|title=Naveen Jindal accuses Zee News of extortion, channel hits back - The Times of India|date=2012-10-25|publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> In July 2018, the Jindal Group withdrew the case against Zee News and both parties to the litigation stated that an out of court settlement had been reached which remains undisclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/ed-charges-against-jindal-others-as-his-firm-settles-case-of-extortion-with-zee/|title=ED charges against Naveen Jindal, others as his firm settles case of extortion with Zee|date=2018-07-14|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of fabrications===\n\n==== Jawaharlal Nehru University sedition controversy ====\n{{main|2016 JNU sedition controversy}}\n''Zee News'' reported that students from the Democratic Students' Union (DSU) raised \"anti-India\" slogans such as ''Bharat ki barbadi'' (Destruction of India) and ''Pakistan Zindabad'' (Long live Pakistan) in an event on the [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] campus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/from-pakistan-zindabad-to-bharat-ki-barbaadi-slogans-that-were-raised-by-anti-nationals-in-jnu_1855562.html|title=From 'Pakistan Zindabad' to 'Bharat ki barbaadi' - Slogans that were raised by 'anti-nationals' in JNU|date=14 February 2016|newspaper=Zee News}}</ref> In a letter Vishwa Deepak, a journalist working at the channel gave a statement that \"our biases made us hear ''Bhartiya Court Zindabad'' (Long live Indian courts) as ''Pakistan Zindabad.''\" Vishwa Deepak later resigned from the channel after expressing reservations over its \"biased coverage\". The footage on the newscast of Zee News had formed the basis of charges filed by the [[Delhi Police]].<ref name=\"TIE-quit2\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/zee-news-producer-quits-video-we-shot-had-no-pakistan-zindabad-slogan/|title=Zee News producer quits: Video we shot had no Pakistan Zindabad slogan|date=22 February 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref> Sudhir Chaudhary, editor and prime time anchor of the channel however on a telecast made a statement saying \"our channel only showed what was happening there, whatever we have shown is 100% authentic.\"<ref name=\"newslaundry-VD2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newslaundry.com/2016/02/21/we-speak-with-the-zee-news-journalist-who-resigned-over-the-channels-coverage-of-junrow/|title=We speak with the Zee News journalist who resigned over the channel's coverage of #JNURow|date=21 February 2016|newspaper=Newslaundry}}</ref> The forensic report of the Delhi Police however later stated that the footage was doctored.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/delhi/story/forensic-experts-say-kanhaiya-video-was-doctored-309626-2016-02-19|title=Forensic experts say Kanhaiya video was doctored|newspaper=India Today|access-date=2019-03-12|agency=Ist|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/delhi/story/forensic-experts-say-kanhaiya-video-was-doctored-309626-2016-02-19|title=JNUSU's Kanhaiya Kumar sedition row: 'Raw footage given by TV channel Doctored, finds Forensic Experts'|date=12 June 2016|work=India Today|accessdate=5 March 2019|agency=Express News Service|language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==== Navjot Singh Sidhu - Alwar controversy ====\nZee News telecasted a video with the claim that the slogans of ''Pakistan Zindabad'' were raised at a rally in [[Alwar]] presided over by the [[Indian National Congress]] politician, [[Navjot Singh Sidhu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/video/india/shocking-pak-supporters-shout-pakistan-zindabad-slogan-in-navjot-singh-sidhu-rally-2160544.html|title=Shocking! Pak supporters shout \"Pakistan Zindabad\" slogan in Navjot Singh Sidhu rally|date=2018-12-03|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Sidhu accused Zee News of playing a doctored video and threatened to file a defamation suit against Zee News.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/to-sue-channel-for-fake-news-sidhu/articleshow/66928000.cms|title=navjot singh sidhu: Will sue channel for fake news: Navjot Singh Sidhu {{!}} Jaipur News - Times of India|last=Mehta|first=Ashish|last2=4 December 2018|date=|website=The Times of India|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 February 2020|last3=|first3=}}</ref> Sidhu stated that slogans of ''[[Bole So Nihal|Jo Bole So Nihal]]'' were misconstrued as being in favor of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/sidhu-to-file-defamation-suit-against-tv-channel-for-airing-fake-video-118120301205_1.html|title=Sidhu to file defamation suit against TV channel for airing 'fake' video|date=2018-12-03|work=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=2020-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> Zee News accused Sidhu of calling a news broadcast to be fake news sent a defamation notice to him. The noticed demanded a apology from him within 24 hours and threatened to pursue legal recourse if an apology was not issued by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/cmcm/zee-news-sends-rs-1000-crore-defamation-notice-to-navjot-singh-sidhu-after-he-accuses-channel-of-playing-fake-video|title=Zee News sends Rs 1000 crore defamation notice to Navjot Singh Sidhu after he accuses channel of playing fake video|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Free Press Journal]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Mahua Moitra criminal defamation case ===\nZee News telecasted a show featuring editor-in-chief [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] where he claimed that [[Trinamool Congress]] legislator [[Mahua Moitra]] had plagiarised author Martin Longman in her maiden speech after being elected to the [[Lok Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/zee-news-falsely-claims-mahua-moitra-plagiarised-her-maiden-parliament-speech/|title=Zee News falsely claims Mahua Moitra plagiarised her maiden Parliament speech|last=Chaudhuri|first=Pooja|date=2019-07-03|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Moitra accused the channel of false reporting  and submitted a breach of privilege motion against Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/mahua-moitra-submits-breach-of-privilege-motion-against-zee-tv-ls-speaker-disallows-it-119070400464_1.html|title=Mahua Moitra submits breach of privilege motion against Zee TV, LS speaker disallows it|date=2019-07-04|work=Business Standard|access-date=2020-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> Martin Longman responded and stated that the legislator did not plagiarise him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/martin-longman-fascism-article-mahua-moitra-1561305-2019-07-03|title=Trinamool MP Mahua Moitra didn't plagiarise: US writer of fascism article shuts trolls|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=3 July 2019|website=[[India Today]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24|last3=|first3=}}</ref> Subsequently, Moitra filed a criminal defamation case against Chaudhary.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/mahua-moitra-criminal-defamation-sudhir-chaudhary|title=Mahua Moitra Files Criminal Defamation Case Against Sudhir Chaudhary|last=|first=|date=|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Coverage of 2020 Delhi election results ===\nThe [[2020 Delhi Legislative Assembly election]] were held on 8 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/elections/assembly-elections/delhi/delhi-election-exit-polls-2020-results-live-news/liveblog/74028057.cms|title=Delhi Election 2020 : Polling held peacefully, counting of votes on February 11|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Economic Times]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The exit poll results predicted the [[Aam Aadmi Party]] to retain their government in [[National capital territory of Delhi|National Capital Territory of Delhi]]. The Zee News telecast of the exit poll results featured Sudhir Chaudhary who indulged in polemic commentary against the voters of the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/plugged-in/primetime/evm-tampering-in-delhi-across-channels-zees-sudhir-chaudhury-angry-at-voters/362327/|title=EVM tampering in Delhi across channels & Zee's Sudhir Chaudhury angry at voters|last=Jha|first=Fiza|date=2020-02-10|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> He stated that the people of Delhi had chosen [[Pakistan]] over [[Hindustan]] and that the rule of [[Mughals]] will now return. He further alleged the people of Delhi are lazy and only concerned about \"freebies\" and that issues like [[Ram Janmabhoomi|Ram Mandir]], [[2019 Balakot airstrike|Balakot airstrike]] and [[Article 370 of the Constitution of India|Revocation of Article 370]] do not matter to them which is why they have rejected the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jansatta.com/national/exit-poll-2020-delhi-election-zee-news-tv-anchor-sudhir-chaudhary-after-exit-poll-out-people-not-worried-about-country/1312191/|title=\u0935\u0940\u0921\u093f\u092f\u094b: \u090f\u0917\u094d\u091c\u093f\u091f \u092a\u094b\u0932 \u092e\u0947\u0902 AAP \u0915\u0940 \u091c\u0940\u0924 \u092a\u0930 \u090f\u0902\u0915\u0930 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0939\u093e- \u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u094b \u0926\u0947\u0936 \u091f\u0942\u091f\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u091a\u093f\u0902\u0924\u093e \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902|last=|first=|date=2020-02-09|website=[[Jansatta]]|language=hi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The telecast resulted in backlash and mockery of Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/how-does-this-qualify-as-journalism-twitter-mocks-zee-news-and-sudhir-chaudhary-for-blaming-delhi-voters-after-exit-polls|title='How does this qualify as journalism?': Twitter mocks Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary for blaming Delhi voters after exit polls|last=|first=|date=9 February 2020|website=[[Free Press Journal]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Sudarshan News]]\n*[[ZEE5]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zeemedia.in Company website]\n* [https://zeenews.india.com/ Channel website]\n\n{{Essel Group}}\n{{Television news in India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zee News}}\n[[Category:24-hour television news channels in India]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Essel Group]]\n[[Category:Zee Entertainment Enterprises]]\n[[Category:Media companies of India]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{See also|Zee TV}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n| launch         = {{Launch date and age|df=y|1999|08|27}}\n| logofile        =Zee News.png\n| logoalt          = \n| owner          = [[Essel Group]]\n| headquarters   =[[Noida]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| picture format = [[1080i]] [[HDTV]]<br />{{small|(downscaled to [[4:3]] [[576i]] for the [[SDTV]] feed)}}\n| broadcast area = International\n| share             =  \n| share as of       = \n| share source      =   \n| sister names = [[Zee TV]]\n| terr serv 1      = [[Oqaab]]<br/>(Afghanistan)\n| terr chan 1      = Channel 45\n| sat serv 1 = [[Airtel Digital TV]]\n| sat chan 1 = Channel 311\n| sat serv 2 = [[Dish TV]]\n| sat chan 2 = Channel 651\n| sat serv 3 = [[Reliance Digital TV]]\n| sat chan 3 = Channel 408\n| sat serv 4 = [[Tata Sky]]\n| sat chan 4 =  Channel 511\n| sat serv 5 = [[Videocon D2H]]\n| sat chan 5 = Channel 302\n| cable serv 1 = [[Siti Cable]]\n| cable chan 1 = Channel 303\n| cable serv 2 = [[Cable TV Hong Kong]]\n| cable chan 2 = Channel 852\n| adsl serv 1 = [[Now TV (China)|now TV]]<br/>(Hong Kong)\n| adsl chan 1 = Channel 785\n| adsl serv 2 = [[Dish Network]]<br/>(United States)\n| adsl chan 2 = Channel 708 (SD)\n| online serv 1    = Live Stream (International)\n| online chan 1    = [http://zeenews.india.com/live-tv live Web stream at Zee News]\n| name = Zee News\n| website = {{URL|https://zeenews.india.com/}}\n| logocaption = \n| logosize =190px \n}}\n\n'''Zee News''' is a [[Hindi language|Hindi-language]] news channel owned by the [[Essel Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esselgroup.com/zee-media-corporation-limited.html|title=Our Companies: Zee Media Corporation Limited|last=|first=|date=|website=esselgroup.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> It is associated with several other sister news channels which provide coverage in Hindi, English and several regional languages of India. Zee News was launched on 27 August 1999 as Zee Sports Ltd. The company was [[Certificate of incorporation|reincorporated]] on 27 May 2004 as Zee News Ltd.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/company/zee-media-27705/information/company-history|title=Zee Media Corporation Ltd.|date=|work=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, Zee News Ltd changed its name to Zee Media Corporation Limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/zee-media-corporation-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-18879.cms|title=Zee Media Corporation History {{!}} Zee Media Corporation Information|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Economic Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The Zee News channel is the flagship channel of the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/stock/zee-media-corporation-ltd_zeenews/reports-directors-report|title=Director Reports, Company Results of Zee Media Corp|last=|first=|date=|website=[[NDTV Profit]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe chairman of the group is [[Subhash Chandra]], who is a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]-backed member of the [[Rajya Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohan|first=Archis|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/politics/subhash-chandra-bets-on-bjp-support-for-rajya-sabha-entry-116053101457_1.html|title=Subhash Chandra bets on BJP support for Rajya Sabha entry|date=2016-06-01|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] is the editor-in-chief of Zee News and the anchor of the prime time show on the channel.<ref name=\"exch1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exchange4media.mobi/tv/sudhir-chaudhary-now-also-editor-in-chief-of-zee-business_68276.html|title=Sudhir Chaudhary now also editor in Chief of zee business|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170715163422/http://www.exchange4media.mobi/tv/sudhir-chaudhary-now-also-editor-in-chief-of-zee-business_68276.html|archive-date=15 July 2017|access-date=15 July 2017|df=}}</ref> The channel has been involved in several controversies and has broadcast fabricated news stories on multiple occasions.<ref name=\"fake\">List of sources:\n\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/book-extract/book-extract-republic-tv-age-of-fake-news-and-promoters-in-indian-tv-newsrooms|title=Book extract: Republic TV, age of fake news and promoters in Indian TV newsrooms|last=Bhushan|first=Sandeep|date=2019-06-29|website=[[National Herald (India)|National Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/read/the-troubling-association-of-zee-and-jlf/article30693362.ece|title=The festival and its funder|last=Jha|first=Aditya Mani|date=2020-01-31|website=[[Business Line]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/zee-news-broadcasts-old-unrelated-satellite-visuals-as-destroyed-jem-camp-in-balakot/|title=Zee News broadcasts old, unrelated satellite visuals as destroyed JEM camp in Balakot|last=Patel|first=Jignesh|date=2019-03-08|website=[[Alt News]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/zee-news-producer-quits-video-we-shot-had-no-pakistan-zindabad-slogan/|title=Zee News producer quits: Video we shot had no Pakistan Zindabad slogan|last=Hafeez|first=Sarah|date=2018-02-22|website=[[The Indian Express]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/india-news-are-newsrooms-run-by-political-masters-why-are-editors-compromising-on-truth-telling/302846|title=Are Newsrooms Run By Political Masters? Why Are Editors Compromising On Truth Telling?|last=Yadav|first=Puneet|date=2020-02-21|website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/hoaxposed/zee-news-tweets-doctored-video-of-navjot-sidhus-rajasthan-rally/158011/|title=Zee News tweets doctored video of Navjot Sidhu\u2019s Rajasthan rally|last=Rampal|first=Nikhil|date=2018-12-03|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.catchnews.com/politics-news/saffron-journalism-zee-news-and-art-of-manufacturing-anti-nationals-1457687402.html|title=Saffron journalism: Zee News & art of manufacturing anti-nationals|last=Menon|first=Aditya|date=10 February 2017|website=catchnews.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/politics/zee-news-subhash-chandra-sudhir-chaudhary-narendra-modi-bhakt-sangh-jnu-bjp-muslims-pakistan-anupam-kher/story/1/9474.html|title=Subhash Chandra failed to convince Zee is not Modi's mouthpiece|last=Khan|first=Saif Ahmed|date=2016-03-10|website=[[India Today|DailyO]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The channel is subjected to an ongoing criminal defamation case against legislator [[Mahua Moitra]] as of March 2020.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Outlets ==\n\n=== Television ===\nThe Zee Media Corporation Limited (ZMCL) operates a number of other channels, some in regional languages with the stated intent of providing a pan-Indian reach.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-profile/ZEEN.BO|title=Profile: Zee Media Corporation Ltd (ZEEN.BO)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Reuters]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/zee-media-to-foray-into-english-news-broadcasting-1512583.html|title=Zee Media to foray into English news broadcasting|last=|first=|date=17 August 2015|website=[[Moneycontrol]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zeemedia.in/channeloverview.html|title=ZMCL Channels Overview|last=|first=|date=|website=www.zeemedia.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''World is One News (WION):''' [[English language]] news channel.\n* '''Zee Business:''' Hindi language business news channel.\n*'''Zee Hindustan:''' 24/7 national Hindi language news channel. It was relaunched in 2017 as an anchor-less news channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/media-tv-news/zee-hindustan-re-launched-as-anchor-less-channel-93472.html|title=Zee Hindustan re-launched as anchor-less channel - Exchange4media|last=|first=|date=|website=exchange4media.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> It was formerly branded as Zee Sangam and India 24x7.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://bestmediainfo.com/2017/05/india-24x7-is-now-zee-hindustan/|title=India 24x7 is now Zee Hindustan|last=|first=|last2=|date=23 May 2017|website=Best Media Info|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=}}</ref>\n* '''Zee 24 Taas:''' 24/7 [[Marathi language]] regional news channel.\n*'''Zee 24 Kalak:''' 24/7 [[Gujarati language]] regional news channel. It was inaugurated on 20 August 2017 by [[Vijay Rupani]], the [[Chief minister (India)|Chief Minister]] of Gujarat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-gujarat-cm-deputy-cm-launch-new-dna-ahmedabad-and-zee-24-kalak-2542970|title=Gujarat CM, Deputy CM launch new DNA Ahmedabad and Zee 24 Kalak|last=|first=|date=2017-09-04|website=[[Zee News|DNA India]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n*'''Zee Rajasthan:''' Hindi language news channel operating in Rajasthan. It was formerly branded as Zee Marudhara.\n*'''Zee Odisha:''' [[Odia language]] regional news channel. It was formerly branded as Zee Kalinga.\n*'''Zee Salaam:''' [[Urdu]] language news channel.\n*'''Zee Madhya Pradesh Chhattisgarh:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Chhattisgarh]].\n*'''Zee Punjab Haryana Himachal:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Haryana]] and [[Himachal Pradesh]].\n*'''Zee Bihar Jharkhand:''' Hindi and [[Bhojpuri language]] news channel operating in Bihar and Jharkhand. It was known as Maurya TV and Zee Purvaiya before the current branding.\n*'''Zee Uttar Pradesh Uttarakhand:''' Hindi language news channel operating in [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Uttarakhand]].\n\nThe company also runs two regional news channels through its subsidiaries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* '''Zee 24 Ghanta:''' 24/7 [[Bengali language]] regional news channel. It is owned by the Zee Akash News Pvt Ltd subsidiary.\n\n[[File:DailyNewsandAnalysisCover.jpg|thumb|Cover of ''Daily News & Analysis''.]]\n\n=== Online ===\nZee News operates the Daily News & Analysis and Zee News websites to provide online coverage of the channel. The Zee5 Website which is owned by the [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises]] is used to platform coverage of other ZMCL channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esselgroup.com/zee-media-corporation-limited.html|title=Zee Media Corporation Limited|last=|first=|date=|website=esselgroup.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The World is One News (WION) channel operates its own WION website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/08/18/zee-english-news-channel_n_8002024.html|title=Zee Group To Launch English News Channel, Hires Rohit Gandhi As Editor-In-Chief|last=Basu|first=Indrani|date=2015-08-18|website=[[Huffington Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> The ZMCL also owns the India.com news website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/cautious-road-ahead-for-zee-entertainment/1787546/|title=Cautious road ahead for Zee Entertainment|last=|first=|date=2019-12-08|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''Zee News Website:''' English and Hindi language online news coverage service of Zee News.\n* '''Daily News & Analysis Website:''' English language online news coverage service. It is branded under the DNA program of Zee News.\n* '''Zee5 Website:''' Streaming service which hosts ZMCL news channels. \n*'''WION Website:''' English language online news coverage service of World is One News.\n*'''India.com:''' English and Hindi language news website owned by ZMCL.\n\n=== Newspaper ===\nThe Daily News & Analysis was an English-language [[broadsheet]] newspaper owned by the Zee Media Corporation Limited. It was launched in 2005 and branded under the Daily News & Analysis (DNA) program of Zee News. It was primarily circulated in [[Mumbai]] and discontinued on 9 October 2019 citing losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/dna-goes-out-of-print-14-years-after-launch-rise-fall-promising-newspaper/304050/|title=DNA goes out of print 14 years after launch \u2014 rise & sudden fall of a promising newspaper|last=Dutta|first=Amrita Nayak|date=2019-10-11|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronosphere.biz/IMO/26/imo.html#dna|title=DNA commissions E&Y to certify circulation|author=Bhupesh Trivedi|date=1 June 2006|work=Indian Media Observer (issue #26)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071219110303/http://www.chronosphere.biz/IMO/26/imo.html#dna|archivedate=19 December 2007|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Jindal Group incident ===\nThe channel was tried for allegedly extorting \u20b9100 [[Crore]] from the [[Jindal Group]] revealed through a sting operation.<ref name=\"The Hindu2\">{{cite news|last=Jebaraj|first=Priscilla|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/jindal-plays-cd-claims-zee-editors-demanded-rs-100-crore/article4031340.ece|title=Jindal plays CD, claims Zee editors demanded Rs. 100 crore|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=4 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Two senior journalists [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] and Sameer Ahluwalia were arrested.<ref name=\"NDTV India2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/naveen-jindal-vs-zee-senior-journalists-arrested-over-alleged-extortion-298095|title=Naveen Jindal vs Zee: Senior journalists arrested over alleged extortion|accessdate=4 December 2014|publisher=NDTV India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/Two-Zee-editors-arrested-for-Rs-100-crore-extortion-bid/articleshow/17391903.cms|title=Two Zee editors arrested for 'Rs 100-crore extortion bid' - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"The Australian2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/jindal-group-and-zee-television-in-extortion-scandal/story-e6frg6so-1226527713986?nk=e835e32ddf2956600de185626015a1b1|title=Jindal Group and Zee television in extortion scandal|accessdate=4 December 2014|publisher=The Australian}}</ref> [[Naveen Jindal]] had accused the two journalists of trying to extort  {{INRConvert|1,000,000,000||lk=on|year=2011}} in advertisements for Zee News from him through blackmail by threatening to air stories against his company in the [[Coalgate scam]]. Zee News denied the charges and made counter claims of Jindal offering them {{INRConvert|200000000||lk=on|year=2011}}  to halt their investigations against [[Jindal Steel]]'s involvement in the scam but filed no charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Naveen-Jindal-accuses-Zee-News-of-extortion-channel-hits-back/articleshow/16956098.cms|title=Naveen Jindal accuses Zee News of extortion, channel hits back - The Times of India|date=2012-10-25|publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> In July 2018, the Jindal Group withdrew the case against Zee News and both parties to the litigation stated that an out of court settlement had been reached which remains undisclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/ed-charges-against-jindal-others-as-his-firm-settles-case-of-extortion-with-zee/|title=ED charges against Naveen Jindal, others as his firm settles case of extortion with Zee|date=2018-07-14|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of fabrications===\n\n==== Jawaharlal Nehru University sedition controversy ====\n{{main|2016 JNU sedition controversy}}\n''Zee News'' reported that students from the Democratic Students' Union (DSU) raised \"anti-India\" slogans such as ''Bharat ki barbadi'' (Destruction of India) and ''Pakistan Zindabad'' (Long live Pakistan) in an event on the [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] campus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/from-pakistan-zindabad-to-bharat-ki-barbaadi-slogans-that-were-raised-by-anti-nationals-in-jnu_1855562.html|title=From 'Pakistan Zindabad' to 'Bharat ki barbaadi' - Slogans that were raised by 'anti-nationals' in JNU|date=14 February 2016|newspaper=Zee News}}</ref> In a letter Vishwa Deepak, a journalist working at the channel gave a statement that \"our biases made us hear ''Bhartiya Court Zindabad'' (Long live Indian courts) as ''Pakistan Zindabad.''\" Vishwa Deepak later resigned from the channel after expressing reservations over its \"biased coverage\". The footage on the newscast of Zee News had formed the basis of charges filed by the [[Delhi Police]].<ref name=\"TIE-quit2\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/zee-news-producer-quits-video-we-shot-had-no-pakistan-zindabad-slogan/|title=Zee News producer quits: Video we shot had no Pakistan Zindabad slogan|date=22 February 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref> Sudhir Chaudhary, editor and prime time anchor of the channel however on a telecast made a statement saying \"our channel only showed what was happening there, whatever we have shown is 100% authentic.\"<ref name=\"newslaundry-VD2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newslaundry.com/2016/02/21/we-speak-with-the-zee-news-journalist-who-resigned-over-the-channels-coverage-of-junrow/|title=We speak with the Zee News journalist who resigned over the channel's coverage of #JNURow|date=21 February 2016|newspaper=Newslaundry}}</ref> The forensic report of the Delhi Police however later stated that the footage was doctored.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/delhi/story/forensic-experts-say-kanhaiya-video-was-doctored-309626-2016-02-19|title=Forensic experts say Kanhaiya video was doctored|newspaper=India Today|access-date=2019-03-12|agency=Ist|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/delhi/story/forensic-experts-say-kanhaiya-video-was-doctored-309626-2016-02-19|title=JNUSU's Kanhaiya Kumar sedition row: 'Raw footage given by TV channel Doctored, finds Forensic Experts'|date=12 June 2016|work=India Today|accessdate=5 March 2019|agency=Express News Service|language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==== GPS Chips in \u20b92000 currency notes ====\nAnchor Sudhir Chaudhary ran a Daily News and Analysis program announcing that the [[Indian 2000-rupee note]] issued after [[2016 Indian banknote demonetisation]] by the government have GPS chips which will allow the government to track currency, thereby reducing corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/821078/no-the-new-rs-2000-note-will-not-have-a-nano-gps-chip-that-can-track-it-anywhere|title=No, the RBI hasn't announced a Rs 2,000 note with a 'nano GPS chip' that it can track|last=Venkataramakrishnan|first=Rohan|date=9 November 2016|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The [[Minister of Finance (India)|Minister of Finance]], [[Arun Jaitley]] dismissed the report as being rumours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/nano-chip-in-rs-2-000-notes-arun-jaitley-dismisses-rumours-1623483|title=Nano Chip In Rs 2,000 Notes? Arun Jaitley Dismisses Rumours|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The [[Reserve Bank of India]] has also given a statement that no such chips are present in the currency notes. The report was classified as a [[hoax]] being circulated on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Raghavan|first=TCA Sharad|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/No-electronic-chip-in-Rs.-2000-notes-RBI/article16440933.ece|title=No electronic chip in Rs. 2000 notes: RBI|date=2016-11-09|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-02-24|url-status=live|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==== Navjot Singh Sidhu - Alwar controversy ====\nZee News telecasted a video with the claim that the slogans of ''Pakistan Zindabad'' were raised at a rally in [[Alwar]] presided over by the [[Indian National Congress]] politician, [[Navjot Singh Sidhu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/video/india/shocking-pak-supporters-shout-pakistan-zindabad-slogan-in-navjot-singh-sidhu-rally-2160544.html|title=Shocking! Pak supporters shout \"Pakistan Zindabad\" slogan in Navjot Singh Sidhu rally|date=2018-12-03|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Sidhu accused Zee News of playing a doctored video and threatened to file a defamation suit against Zee News.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/to-sue-channel-for-fake-news-sidhu/articleshow/66928000.cms|title=navjot singh sidhu: Will sue channel for fake news: Navjot Singh Sidhu {{!}} Jaipur News - Times of India|last=Mehta|first=Ashish|last2=4 December 2018|date=|website=The Times of India|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 February 2020|last3=|first3=}}</ref> Sidhu stated that slogans of ''[[Bole So Nihal|Jo Bole So Nihal]]'' were misconstrued as being in favor of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/sidhu-to-file-defamation-suit-against-tv-channel-for-airing-fake-video-118120301205_1.html|title=Sidhu to file defamation suit against TV channel for airing 'fake' video|date=2018-12-03|work=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=2020-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> Zee News accused Sidhu of calling a news broadcast to be fake news sent a defamation notice to him. The noticed demanded a apology from him within 24 hours and threatened to pursue legal recourse if an apology was not issued by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/cmcm/zee-news-sends-rs-1000-crore-defamation-notice-to-navjot-singh-sidhu-after-he-accuses-channel-of-playing-fake-video|title=Zee News sends Rs 1000 crore defamation notice to Navjot Singh Sidhu after he accuses channel of playing fake video|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Free Press Journal]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Mahua Moitra criminal defamation case ===\nZee News telecasted a show featuring editor-in-chief [[Sudhir Chaudhary (journalist)|Sudhir Chaudhary]] where he claimed that [[Trinamool Congress]] legislator [[Mahua Moitra]] had plagiarised author Martin Longman in her maiden speech after being elected to the [[Lok Sabha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/zee-news-falsely-claims-mahua-moitra-plagiarised-her-maiden-parliament-speech/|title=Zee News falsely claims Mahua Moitra plagiarised her maiden Parliament speech|last=Chaudhuri|first=Pooja|date=2019-07-03|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Moitra accused the channel of false reporting  and submitted a breach of privilege motion against Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/mahua-moitra-submits-breach-of-privilege-motion-against-zee-tv-ls-speaker-disallows-it-119070400464_1.html|title=Mahua Moitra submits breach of privilege motion against Zee TV, LS speaker disallows it|date=2019-07-04|work=Business Standard|access-date=2020-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> Martin Longman responded and stated that the legislator did not plagiarise him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/martin-longman-fascism-article-mahua-moitra-1561305-2019-07-03|title=Trinamool MP Mahua Moitra didn't plagiarise: US writer of fascism article shuts trolls|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=3 July 2019|website=[[India Today]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24|last3=|first3=}}</ref> Subsequently, Moitra filed a criminal defamation case against Chaudhary.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/mahua-moitra-criminal-defamation-sudhir-chaudhary|title=Mahua Moitra Files Criminal Defamation Case Against Sudhir Chaudhary|last=|first=|date=|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Coverage of 2020 Delhi election results ===\nThe [[2020 Delhi Legislative Assembly election]] were held on 8 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/elections/assembly-elections/delhi/delhi-election-exit-polls-2020-results-live-news/liveblog/74028057.cms|title=Delhi Election 2020 : Polling held peacefully, counting of votes on February 11|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Economic Times]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The exit poll results predicted the [[Aam Aadmi Party]] to retain their government in [[National capital territory of Delhi|National Capital Territory of Delhi]]. The Zee News telecast of the exit poll results featured Sudhir Chaudhary who indulged in polemic commentary against the voters of the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/plugged-in/primetime/evm-tampering-in-delhi-across-channels-zees-sudhir-chaudhury-angry-at-voters/362327/|title=EVM tampering in Delhi across channels & Zee's Sudhir Chaudhury angry at voters|last=Jha|first=Fiza|date=2020-02-10|website=[[ThePrint]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> He stated that the people of Delhi had chosen [[Pakistan]] over [[Hindustan]] and that the rule of [[Mughals]] will now return. He further alleged the people of Delhi are lazy and only concerned about \"freebies\" and that issues like [[Ram Janmabhoomi|Ram Mandir]], [[2019 Balakot airstrike|Balakot airstrike]] and [[Article 370 of the Constitution of India|Revocation of Article 370]] do not matter to them which is why they have rejected the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jansatta.com/national/exit-poll-2020-delhi-election-zee-news-tv-anchor-sudhir-chaudhary-after-exit-poll-out-people-not-worried-about-country/1312191/|title=\u0935\u0940\u0921\u093f\u092f\u094b: \u090f\u0917\u094d\u091c\u093f\u091f \u092a\u094b\u0932 \u092e\u0947\u0902 AAP \u0915\u0940 \u091c\u0940\u0924 \u092a\u0930 \u090f\u0902\u0915\u0930 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0939\u093e- \u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u094b \u0926\u0947\u0936 \u091f\u0942\u091f\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u091a\u093f\u0902\u0924\u093e \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902|last=|first=|date=2020-02-09|website=[[Jansatta]]|language=hi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The telecast resulted in backlash and mockery of Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/how-does-this-qualify-as-journalism-twitter-mocks-zee-news-and-sudhir-chaudhary-for-blaming-delhi-voters-after-exit-polls|title='How does this qualify as journalism?': Twitter mocks Zee News and Sudhir Chaudhary for blaming Delhi voters after exit polls|last=|first=|date=9 February 2020|website=[[Free Press Journal]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Sudarshan News]]\n*[[ZEE5]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zeemedia.in Company website]\n* [https://zeenews.india.com/ Channel website]\n\n{{Essel Group}}\n{{Television news in India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zee News}}\n[[Category:24-hour television news channels in India]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Essel Group]]\n[[Category:Zee Entertainment Enterprises]]\n[[Category:Media companies of India]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of India]]\n", "name_user": "Chris Syd29", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Incorrect details removed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zee_News"}
{"title_page": "Histone deacetylase inhibitor", "text_new": "'''Histone deacetylase inhibitors''' ('''HDAC inhibitors''', '''HDACi''', '''HDIs''') are chemical compounds that [[enzyme inhibitor|inhibit]] [[histone deacetylase]]s.\n\nHDIs have a long history of use in psychiatry and neurology as mood stabilizers and anti-epileptics. More recently they are being investigated as possible treatments for cancers,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Miller TA, Witter DJ, Belvedere S | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors | journal = Journal of Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 46 | issue = 24 | pages = 5097\u2013116 | date = November 2003 | pmid = 14613312 | doi = 10.1021/jm0303094 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mwakwari SC, Patil V, Guerrant W, Oyelere AK | title = Macrocyclic histone deacetylase inhibitors | journal = Current Topics in Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 10 | issue = 14 | pages = 1423\u201340 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20536416 | pmc = 3144151 | doi = 10.2174/156802610792232079 }}</ref> parasitic<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Patil V, Guerrant W, Chen PC, Gryder B, Benicewicz DB, Khan SI, Tekwani BL, Oyelere AK | title = Antimalarial and antileishmanial activities of histone deacetylase inhibitors with triazole-linked cap group | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 415\u201325 | date = January 2010 | pmid = 19914074 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmc.2009.10.042 | pmc=2818366}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beus|first=Maja|last2=Raji\u0107|first2=Zrinka|last3=Maysinger|first3=Dusica|last4=Mlinari\u0107|first4=Zvonimir|last5=Antunovi\u0107|first5=Maja|last6=Marijanovi\u0107|first6=Inga|last7=Fontinha|first7=Diana|last8=Prud\u00eancio|first8=Miguel|last9=Held|first9=Jana|last10=Olgen|first10=Sureyya|last11=Zorc|first11=Branka|date=2018-08-01|title=SAHAquines, Novel Hybrids Based on SAHA and Primaquine Motifs, as Potential Cytostatic and Antiplasmodial Agents|url=https://chemistry-europe.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/open.201800117|journal=ChemistryOpen|volume=7|issue=8|pages=624\u2013638|doi=10.1002/open.201800117|issn=2191-1363|pmc=PMC6104433|pmid=30151334}}</ref>and inflammatory diseases.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blanchard F, Chipoy C | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: new drugs for the treatment of inflammatory diseases? | journal = Drug Discovery Today | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 197\u2013204 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15708534 | doi = 10.1016/S1359-6446(04)03309-4 }}</ref>\n\n== Cellular biochemistry/pharmacology ==\nTo carry out gene expression, a cell must control the coiling and uncoiling of DNA around [[histones]].  This is accomplished with the assistance of [[histone acetyltransferase|histone acetyl transferases]] (HAT), which acetylate the lysine residues in core histones leading to a less compact and more transcriptionally active [[chromatin]], and, on the converse, the actions of [[histone deacetylases]] (HDAC), which remove the acetyl groups from the lysine residues leading to the formation of a condensed and transcriptionally silenced chromatin. Reversible modification of the terminal tails of core histones constitutes the major [[epigenetic]] mechanism for remodeling higher-order chromatin structure and controlling [[gene expression]].  HDAC inhibitors (HDI) block this action and can result in hyperacetylation of histones, thereby affecting gene expression.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thiagalingam S, Cheng KH, Lee HJ, Mineva N, Thiagalingam A, Ponte JF | title = Histone deacetylases: unique players in shaping the epigenetic histone code | journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences | volume = 983 | issue = 1 | pages = 84\u2013100 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12724214 | doi = 10.1111/j.1749-6632.2003.tb05964.x | bibcode = 2003NYASA.983...84T }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marks PA, Richon VM, Rifkind RA | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: inducers of differentiation or apoptosis of transformed cells | journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute | volume = 92 | issue = 15 | pages = 1210\u20136 | date = August 2000 | pmid = 10922406 | doi = 10.1093/jnci/92.15.1210 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17951399\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dokmanovic M, Clarke C, Marks PA | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: overview and perspectives | journal = Molecular Cancer Research | volume = 5 | issue = 10 | pages = 981\u20139 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17951399 | doi = 10.1158/1541-7786.MCR-07-0324 }}</ref> The open chromatin resulting from inhibition of histone deacetylases can result in either the up-regulation or the repression of genes.<ref name=\"pmid17951399\" />\n\nThe histone deacetylase inhibitors are a new class of cytostatic agents that inhibit the proliferation of tumor cells in culture and in vivo by inducing cell cycle arrest, differentiation and/or apoptosis. Histone deacetylase inhibitors exert their anti-tumour effects via the induction of expression changes of oncogenes or tumour suppressor, through modulating the acetylation/deactylation of histones and/or non-histone proteins such as transcription factors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chueh AC, Tse JW, T\u00f6gel L, Mariadason JM | title = Mechanisms of Histone Deacetylase Inhibitor-Regulated Gene Expression in Cancer Cells | journal = Antioxidants & Redox Signaling | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = 66\u201384 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 24512308 | doi = 10.1089/ars.2014.5863 | pmc = 4492771 }}</ref> Histone acetylation and deacetylation play important roles in the modulation of chromatin topology and the regulation of gene transcription. Histone deacetylase inhibition induces the accumulation of hyperacetylated nucleosome core histones in most regions of chromatin but affects the expression of only a small subset of genes, leading to transcriptional activation of some genes, but repression of an equal or larger number of other genes. Non-histone proteins such as transcription factors are also targets for acetylation with varying functional effects. Acetylation enhances the activity of some transcription factors such as the tumor suppressor p53 and the erythroid differentiation factor GATA-1 but may repress transcriptional activity of others including T cell factor and the co-activator ACTR. Recent studies [...] have shown that the estrogen receptor alpha (ERalpha) can be hyperacetylated in response to histone deacetylase inhibition, suppressing ligand sensitivity and regulating transcriptional activation by histone deacetylase inhibitors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gryder BE, Rood MK, Johnson KA, Patil V, Raftery ED, Yao LP, Rice M, Azizi B, Doyle DF, Oyelere AK | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors equipped with estrogen receptor modulation activity | journal = Journal of Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 56 | issue = 14 | pages = 5782\u201396 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23786452 | doi = 10.1021/jm400467w | pmc=3812312}}</ref> Conservation of the acetylated ER-alpha motif in other nuclear receptors suggests that acetylation may play an important regulatory role in diverse nuclear receptor signaling functions. A number of structurally diverse histone deacetylase inhibitors have shown potent antitumor efficacy with little toxicity in vivo in animal models. Several compounds are currently in early phase clinical development as potential treatments for solid and hematological cancers both as monotherapy and in combination with cytotoxics and differentiation agents.\"<ref name=Vigushin2004>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vigushin DM, Coombes RC | title = Targeted histone deacetylase inhibition for cancer therapy | journal = [[Current Cancer Drug Targets]] | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages = 205\u201318 | date = March 2004 | pmid = 15032670 | doi = 10.2174/1568009043481560 }}</ref>\n\n=== HDAC classification ===\nBased on their homology of accessory domains to [[yeast]] histone deacetylases, the 18 currently known human histone deacetylases are classified into four groups (I-IV):<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hdacis.com/index.html | title = Histone deacetylase (HDAC) Inhibitors Database|work=hdacis.com | accessdate = 6 October 2015 }}</ref>\n*Class I, which includes [[HDAC1]], [[HDAC2|-2]], [[HDAC3|-3]] and [[HDAC8|-8]] are related to yeast RPD3 gene;\n*Class IIA, which includes [[HDAC4]], [[HDAC5|-5]], -7 and [[HDAC9|-9]]; Class IIB [[HDAC6|-6]], and [[HDAC10|-10]] are related to yeast Hda1 gene;\n*Class III, also known as the [[sirtuins]] are related to the Sir2 gene and include SIRT1-7\n*Class IV, which contains only [[HDAC11]] has features of both Class I and II.\n\n=== HDI classification ===\nThe \"classical\" HDIs act exclusively on Class I, II and Class IV HDACs by binding to the zinc-containing catalytic domain of the HDACs.  These classical HDIs can be classified into several groupings named according to the chemical moiety that binds to the zinc ion (except cyclic tetrapeptides which bind to the zinc ion with a thiol group). Some examples in decreasing order of the typical zinc binding affinity:<ref name=Drummond05>{{cite journal | vauthors = Drummond DC, Noble CO, Kirpotin DB, Guo Z, Scott GK, Benz CC | title = Clinical development of histone deacetylase inhibitors as anticancer agents | journal = Annual Review of Pharmacology and Toxicology | volume = 45 | pages = 495\u2013528 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15822187 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.pharmtox.45.120403.095825 }}</ref>\n# [[hydroxamic acid]]s (or hydroxamates), such as [[trichostatin A]],\n# cyclic tetrapeptides (such as trapoxin B), and the [[depsipeptide]]s,\n# [[benzamide]]s,\n# electrophilic [[ketone]]s, and\n# the [[aliphatic]] acid compounds such as [[Sodium phenylbutyrate|phenylbutyrate]] and [[valproic acid]].\n\n\"Second-generation\" HDIs include the hydroxamic acids [[vorinostat]] (SAHA), [[belinostat]] (PXD101), [[LAQ824]], and [[panobinostat]] (LBH589); and the [[benzamide]]s : [[entinostat]] (MS-275), [[tacedinaline]] (CI994), and [[mocetinostat]] (MGCD0103).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beckers T, Burkhardt C, Wieland H, Gimmnich P, Ciossek T, Maier T, Sanders K | title = Distinct pharmacological properties of second generation HDAC inhibitors with the benzamide or hydroxamate head group | journal = International Journal of Cancer | volume = 121 | issue = 5 | pages = 1138\u201348 | date = September 2007 | pmid = 17455259 | doi = 10.1002/ijc.22751 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid15955865\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Acharya MR, Sparreboom A, Venitz J, Figg WD | title = Rational development of histone deacetylase inhibitors as anticancer agents: a review | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 68 | issue = 4 | pages = 917\u201332 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 15955865 | doi = 10.1124/mol.105.014167 }}</ref>\n\nThe sirtuin Class III HDACs are dependent on NAD+ and are, therefore, inhibited by [[nicotinamide]], as well as derivatives of NAD, dihydrocoumarin, naphthopyranone, and 2-hydroxynaphthaldehydes.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Porcu M, Chiarugi A | title = The emerging therapeutic potential of sirtuin-interacting drugs: from cell death to lifespan extension | journal = Trends in Pharmacological Sciences | volume = 26 | issue = 2 | pages = 94\u2013103 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15681027 | doi = 10.1016/j.tips.2004.12.009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Additional functions ===\nHDIs should not be considered to act solely as enzyme inhibitors of HDACs.  A large variety of nonhistone transcription factors and transcriptional co-regulators are known to be modified by acetylation.  HDIs can alter the degree of acetylation nonhistone effector molecules and, therefore, increase or repress the transcription of genes by this mechanism.  Examples include: [[Nuclear receptor coactivator 3|ACTR]], cMyb, [[E2F1]], [[EKLF]], FEN 1, [[GATA transcription factor|GATA]], HNF-4, [[HSP90]], [[Ku70]], [[MKP-1]], [[NF-\u03baB]], [[PCNA]], p53, [[Retinoblastoma protein|RB]], Runx, SF1 Sp3, [[STAT protein|STAT]], [[TFIIE]], [[T-cell|TCF]], [[YY1]], etc.<ref name=Drummond05 /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yang XJ, Seto E | title = HATs and HDACs: from structure, function and regulation to novel strategies for therapy and prevention | journal = Oncogene | volume = 26 | issue = 37 | pages = 5310\u20138 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17694074 | doi = 10.1038/sj.onc.1210599}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Jeong Y, Du R, Zhu X, Yin S, Wang J, Cui H, Cao W, Lowenstein CJ | title = Histone deacetylase isoforms regulate innate immune responses by deacetylating mitogen-activated protein kinase phosphatase-1 | journal = J Leukoc Biol | volume = 95 | issue = 4 | pages = 651\u20139 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24374966 | doi = 10.1189/jlb.1013565}}</ref>\n\n== Uses ==\n\n=== Psychiatry and neurology ===\nHDIs have a long history of use in psychiatry and neurology as mood stabilizers and anti-epileptics.  The prime example of this is [[valproic acid]], marketed as a drug under the trade names ''Depakene'', ''Depakote'', and ''Divalproex''.  In more recent times, HDIs are being studied as a mitigator for [[neurodegenerative diseases]] such as [[Alzheimer's disease]] and [[Huntington's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hahnen E, Hauke J, Tr\u00e4nkle C, Ey\u00fcpoglu IY, Wirth B, Bl\u00fcmcke I | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: possible implications for neurodegenerative disorders | journal = Expert Opinion on Investigational Drugs | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 169\u201384 | date = February 2008 | pmid = 18230051 | doi = 10.1517/13543784.17.2.169 }}</ref>\nEnhancement of memory formation is increased in mice given [[vorinostat]], or by genetic knockout of the HDAC2 gene in mice.<ref name=\"pmid19424149\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Guan JS, Haggarty SJ, Giacometti E, Dannenberg JH, Joseph N, Gao J, Nieland TJ, Zhou Y, Wang X, Mazitschek R, Bradner JE, DePinho RA, Jaenisch R, Tsai LH | title = HDAC2 negatively regulates memory formation and synaptic plasticity | journal = Nature | volume = 459 | issue = 7243 | pages = 55\u201360 | date = May 2009 | pmid = 19424149 | pmc = 3498958 | doi = 10.1038/nature07925 | bibcode = 2009Natur.459...55G }}</ref>\nWhile that may have relevance to Alzheimer's disease, it was shown that some cognitive deficits were restored in actual transgenic mice that have a model of Alzheimer's disease (3xTg-AD) by orally administered nicotinamide, a competitive HDI of Class III sirtuins.<ref name=\"pmid18987186\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Green KN, Steffan JS, Martinez-Coria H, Sun X, Schreiber SS, Thompson LM, LaFerla FM | title = Nicotinamide restores cognition in Alzheimer's disease transgenic mice via a mechanism involving sirtuin inhibition and selective reduction of Thr231-phosphotau | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 28 | issue = 45 | pages = 11500\u201310 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18987186 | pmc = 2617713 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3203-08.2008 }}</ref>\n\n==== Pre Clinical Research \u2013 HDI therapy for the treatment of depression ====\nRecent research into the causes of [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] has highlighted some possible [[gene-environment interaction]]s that could explain why after much research, no specific genes or loci which would indicate risk for depression have emerged.<ref name=\"schroeder\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schroeder M, Hillemacher T, Bleich S, Frieling H | title = The epigenetic code in depression: implications for treatment | journal = Clinical Pharmacology and Therapeutics | volume = 91 | issue = 2 | pages = 310\u20134 | date = February 2012 | pmid = 22205200 | doi = 10.1038/clpt.2011.282  }}</ref> Recent studies estimate that even after successive treatments with multiple antidepressants, almost 35% of patients did not achieve remission,<ref name=\"fuchikami\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fuchikami M, Yamamoto S, Morinobu S, Okada S, Yamawaki Y, Yamawaki S | title = The potential use of histone deacetylase inhibitors in the treatment of depression | journal = Progress in Neuro-Psychopharmacology & Biological Psychiatry | volume = 64 | pages = 320\u20134 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 25818247 | doi = 10.1016/j.pnpbp.2015.03.010  }}</ref> suggesting that there could be an epigenetic component to depression that is not being addressed by current pharmacological treatments. Environmental stressors, namely traumatic stress in childhood such as maternal deprivation and early childhood abuse have been studied for their connection to a high risk of depression in adulthood. In animal models, these types of trauma have been shown to have significant effects on [[Histone acetylation and deacetylation|histone acetylation]], particularly at gene [[Locus (genetics)|loci]] which have known connection to behavior and mood regulation.<ref name=\"schroeder\" /><ref name=\"machado\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Machado-Vieira R, Ibrahim L, Zarate CA | title = Histone deacetylases and mood disorders: epigenetic programming in gene-environment interactions | journal = CNS Neuroscience & Therapeutics | volume = 17 | issue = 6 | pages = 699\u2013704 | date = December 2011 | pmid = 20961400 | pmc = 3026916 | doi = 10.1111/j.1755-5949.2010.00203.X }}</ref> Current research has focused on the use of HDI therapy for depression after studies on depressed patients in the middle of a depressive episode found increased expression of HDAC2 and HDAC5 [[mRNA]] compared to controls and patients in remission.<ref name=\"machado\" />\n\n===== Effects on gene expression =====\nVarious HDAC inhibitors (HDI) have been studied for their connection to the regulation of mood and behavior, each having different, specific effects on the regulation of various genes. The most commonly studied genes include [[Brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) and [[Glial cell line-derived neurotrophic factor]] (GDNF) both of which help regulate [[neuron]] growth and health, whose down regulation can be a symptom of depression.<ref name=\"machado\" /> Multiple studies have shown that treatment with an HDI helps to up regulate expression of BDNF: valproic acid (commonly used to treat epilepsy and bipolar disorder)<ref name=\"fuchikami\" /> as well as [[sodium butyrate]]<ref name=\"machado\" /> both increased expression of BDNF in animal models of depression. One study which traced GDNF levels in the [[ventral striatum]] found increased gene expression upon treatment with [[Vorinostat|SAHA]].<ref name=\"fuchikami\" />\n\n===== Effects on depressive behaviors =====\nPre-clinical research on the use of HDAC inhibitors (HDI) for the treatment of depression use rodents to model human depression. The [[tail suspension test]] (TST) and the [[forced swimming test]] (FST) measure the level of defeat in rodents\u2014 usually after treatment with chronic stress\u2014 which mirrors symptoms of human depression. Alongside tests for levels of HDAC mRNA, acetylation and gene expression these behavioral tests are compared to controls to determine whether or not treatment with an HDI has been successful in ameliorating symptoms of depression. Studies which used [[Vorinostat|SAHA]] or [[Entinostat|MS-275]] as their treatment compound found treated animals displayed gene expression profiles similar to those treated with [[Prozac|fluoxetine]], and displayed similar anti-depressant like behavior.<ref name=\"schroeder\" /><ref name =\"fuchikami\" /><ref name=\"machado\" /> Sodium butyrate is commonly used as a candidate for mood disorder treatment: studies using it both alone and in co-treatment with [[Prozac|fluoxetine]] report subjects with increased performance on both TST and FST<ref name=\"fuchikami\" /> in addition to increased expression of BDNF.<ref name=\"machado\" />\n\n=== Cancer treatment ===\n\n=== Inflammatory diseases ===\n[[Trichostatin A]] (TSA) and others are being investigated as anti-inflammatory agents.<ref name=Adcock2007>{{cite journal | vauthors = Adcock IM | title = HDAC inhibitors as anti-inflammatory agents | journal = British Journal of Pharmacology | volume = 150 | issue = 7 | pages = 829\u201331 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17325655 | pmc = 2013887 | doi = 10.1038/sj.bjp.0707166 }}</ref>\n\n=== HIV/AIDS ===\nAfter the successful initial round of ''in vitro'' research in January 2013, the [[Danish Research Council]] awarded the research team led by Dr. Ole S\u00f8gaard from the Danish [[Aarhus University Hospital]] the amount of $2 million to proceed with clinical trials on 15 humans. The goal is for HDAC inhibitors to flush HIV from the reservoirs it builds within the DNA of infected cells, followed by a vaccination to help the immune system to neutralize any replicating virus.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gayomali |first=Chris |title=Breakthrough: Is an HIV cure just a few months away? |newspaper=The Week |publisher=The Week Publications |date=April 29, 2013 |url=http://theweek.com/article/index/243402/breakthrough-is-an-hiv-cure-just-a-few-months-away |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOne study noted the use of [[panobinostat]], [[entinostat]], [[romidepsin]], and [[vorinostat]] specifically for the purpose of reactivating latent HIV in order to diminish the reservoirs. Vorinostat was noted as the least potent of the HDAC inhibitors in this trial.<ref name=\"pmid25393648\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Elliott JH, Wightman F, Solomon A, Ghneim K, Ahlers J, Cameron MJ, Smith MZ, Spelman T, McMahon J, Velayudham P, Brown G, Roney J, Watson J, Prince MH, Hoy JF, Chomont N, Fromentin R, Procopio FA, Zeidan J, Palmer S, Odevall L, Johnstone RW, Martin BP, Sinclair E, Deeks SG, Hazuda DJ, Cameron PU, S\u00e9kaly RP, Lewin SR | name-list-format = vanc  | title = Activation of HIV transcription with short-course vorinostat in HIV-infected patients on suppressive antiretroviral therapy | journal = PLoS Pathogens | volume = 10 | issue = 11 | pages = e1004473 | year = 2014 | pmid = 25393648 | pmc = 4231123 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1004473 }}</ref> Another study found that romidepsin led to a higher and more sustained level of cell-associated HIV RNA reactivation than vorinostat in latently infected T-cells [[in vitro]] and [[ex vivo]].<ref name=\"pmid24722454\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wei DG, Chiang V, Fyne E, Balakrishnan M, Barnes T, Graupe M, Hesselgesser J, Irrinki A, Murry JP, Stepan G, Stray KM, Tsai A, Yu H, Spindler J, Kearney M, Spina CA, McMahon D, Lalezari J, Sloan D, Mellors J, Geleziunas R, Cihlar T | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitor romidepsin induces HIV expression in CD4 T cells from patients on suppressive antiretroviral therapy at concentrations achieved by clinical dosing | journal = PLoS Pathogens | volume = 10 | issue = 4 | pages = e1004071 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24722454 | pmc = 3983056 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1004071 }}</ref>\n\n=== Other diseases ===\n*[[Givinostat]] (ITF2357) is also under investigation for treatment of [[polycythemia vera]] (PV), [[essential thrombocythemia]] (ET) and [[myelofibrosis]] (MF).\n\nHDIs are also being studied as protection of heart muscle in [[acute myocardial infarction]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Granger A, Abdullah I, Huebner F, Stout A, Wang T, Huebner T, Epstein JA, Gruber PJ | title = Histone deacetylase inhibition reduces myocardial ischemia-reperfusion injury in mice | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 22 | issue = 10 | pages = 3549\u201360 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18606865 | pmc = 2537432 | doi = 10.1096/fj.08-108548 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite patent |country=HK |number=1124320 |status=application |title=Novel Sulphonylpyrroles as Inhibitors of Hdac S Novel Sulphonylpyrroles |pubdate=October 22, 2009 |fdate=September 8, 2006 |pridate=September 21, 2005 |inventor=Maier, Thomas; Beckers, Thomas; Hummel, Rolf-Peter; Feth, Martin; M\u00fcller, Matthias; B\u00e4r, Thomas; Volz, J\u00fcrgen}}\n* [http://www.hdacis.com/ HDAC inhibitors base] information about molecules that block HDACs.\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Tambunan US, Wulandari EK | title = Identification of a better Homo sapiens Class II HDAC inhibitor through binding energy calculations and descriptor analysis | journal = BMC Bioinformatics | volume = 11 Suppl 7 | pages = S16 | year = 2010 | pmid = 21106123 | pmc = 2957684 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2105-11-S7-S16 }}\n\n{{HDAC inhibitors}}\n{{Enzyme inhibition}}\n\n[[Category:Histone deacetylase inhibitors| ]]\n[[Category:Antineoplastic drugs]]\n[[Category:Mood stabilizers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Histone deacetylase inhibitors''' ('''HDAC inhibitors''', '''HDACi''', '''HDIs''') are chemical compounds that [[enzyme inhibitor|inhibit]] [[histone deacetylase]]s.\n\nHDIs have a long history of use in psychiatry and neurology as mood stabilizers and anti-epileptics. More recently they are being investigated as possible treatments for cancers,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Miller TA, Witter DJ, Belvedere S | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors | journal = Journal of Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 46 | issue = 24 | pages = 5097\u2013116 | date = November 2003 | pmid = 14613312 | doi = 10.1021/jm0303094 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mwakwari SC, Patil V, Guerrant W, Oyelere AK | title = Macrocyclic histone deacetylase inhibitors | journal = Current Topics in Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 10 | issue = 14 | pages = 1423\u201340 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20536416 | pmc = 3144151 | doi = 10.2174/156802610792232079 }}</ref> parasitic<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Patil V, Guerrant W, Chen PC, Gryder B, Benicewicz DB, Khan SI, Tekwani BL, Oyelere AK | title = Antimalarial and antileishmanial activities of histone deacetylase inhibitors with triazole-linked cap group | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 415\u201325 | date = January 2010 | pmid = 19914074 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmc.2009.10.042 | pmc=2818366}}</ref> and inflammatory diseases.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blanchard F, Chipoy C | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: new drugs for the treatment of inflammatory diseases? | journal = Drug Discovery Today | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 197\u2013204 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15708534 | doi = 10.1016/S1359-6446(04)03309-4 }}</ref>\n\n== Cellular biochemistry/pharmacology ==\nTo carry out gene expression, a cell must control the coiling and uncoiling of DNA around [[histones]].  This is accomplished with the assistance of [[histone acetyltransferase|histone acetyl transferases]] (HAT), which acetylate the lysine residues in core histones leading to a less compact and more transcriptionally active [[chromatin]], and, on the converse, the actions of [[histone deacetylases]] (HDAC), which remove the acetyl groups from the lysine residues leading to the formation of a condensed and transcriptionally silenced chromatin. Reversible modification of the terminal tails of core histones constitutes the major [[epigenetic]] mechanism for remodeling higher-order chromatin structure and controlling [[gene expression]].  HDAC inhibitors (HDI) block this action and can result in hyperacetylation of histones, thereby affecting gene expression.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thiagalingam S, Cheng KH, Lee HJ, Mineva N, Thiagalingam A, Ponte JF | title = Histone deacetylases: unique players in shaping the epigenetic histone code | journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences | volume = 983 | issue = 1 | pages = 84\u2013100 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12724214 | doi = 10.1111/j.1749-6632.2003.tb05964.x | bibcode = 2003NYASA.983...84T }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Marks PA, Richon VM, Rifkind RA | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: inducers of differentiation or apoptosis of transformed cells | journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute | volume = 92 | issue = 15 | pages = 1210\u20136 | date = August 2000 | pmid = 10922406 | doi = 10.1093/jnci/92.15.1210 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17951399\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dokmanovic M, Clarke C, Marks PA | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: overview and perspectives | journal = Molecular Cancer Research | volume = 5 | issue = 10 | pages = 981\u20139 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17951399 | doi = 10.1158/1541-7786.MCR-07-0324 }}</ref> The open chromatin resulting from inhibition of histone deacetylases can result in either the up-regulation or the repression of genes.<ref name=\"pmid17951399\" />\n\nThe histone deacetylase inhibitors are a new class of cytostatic agents that inhibit the proliferation of tumor cells in culture and in vivo by inducing cell cycle arrest, differentiation and/or apoptosis. Histone deacetylase inhibitors exert their anti-tumour effects via the induction of expression changes of oncogenes or tumour suppressor, through modulating the acetylation/deactylation of histones and/or non-histone proteins such as transcription factors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chueh AC, Tse JW, T\u00f6gel L, Mariadason JM | title = Mechanisms of Histone Deacetylase Inhibitor-Regulated Gene Expression in Cancer Cells | journal = Antioxidants & Redox Signaling | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = 66\u201384 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 24512308 | doi = 10.1089/ars.2014.5863 | pmc = 4492771 }}</ref> Histone acetylation and deacetylation play important roles in the modulation of chromatin topology and the regulation of gene transcription. Histone deacetylase inhibition induces the accumulation of hyperacetylated nucleosome core histones in most regions of chromatin but affects the expression of only a small subset of genes, leading to transcriptional activation of some genes, but repression of an equal or larger number of other genes. Non-histone proteins such as transcription factors are also targets for acetylation with varying functional effects. Acetylation enhances the activity of some transcription factors such as the tumor suppressor p53 and the erythroid differentiation factor GATA-1 but may repress transcriptional activity of others including T cell factor and the co-activator ACTR. Recent studies [...] have shown that the estrogen receptor alpha (ERalpha) can be hyperacetylated in response to histone deacetylase inhibition, suppressing ligand sensitivity and regulating transcriptional activation by histone deacetylase inhibitors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gryder BE, Rood MK, Johnson KA, Patil V, Raftery ED, Yao LP, Rice M, Azizi B, Doyle DF, Oyelere AK | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors equipped with estrogen receptor modulation activity | journal = Journal of Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 56 | issue = 14 | pages = 5782\u201396 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23786452 | doi = 10.1021/jm400467w | pmc=3812312}}</ref> Conservation of the acetylated ER-alpha motif in other nuclear receptors suggests that acetylation may play an important regulatory role in diverse nuclear receptor signaling functions. A number of structurally diverse histone deacetylase inhibitors have shown potent antitumor efficacy with little toxicity in vivo in animal models. Several compounds are currently in early phase clinical development as potential treatments for solid and hematological cancers both as monotherapy and in combination with cytotoxics and differentiation agents.\"<ref name=Vigushin2004>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vigushin DM, Coombes RC | title = Targeted histone deacetylase inhibition for cancer therapy | journal = [[Current Cancer Drug Targets]] | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages = 205\u201318 | date = March 2004 | pmid = 15032670 | doi = 10.2174/1568009043481560 }}</ref>\n\n=== HDAC classification ===\nBased on their homology of accessory domains to [[yeast]] histone deacetylases, the 18 currently known human histone deacetylases are classified into four groups (I-IV):<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hdacis.com/index.html | title = Histone deacetylase (HDAC) Inhibitors Database|work=hdacis.com | accessdate = 6 October 2015 }}</ref>\n*Class I, which includes [[HDAC1]], [[HDAC2|-2]], [[HDAC3|-3]] and [[HDAC8|-8]] are related to yeast RPD3 gene;\n*Class IIA, which includes [[HDAC4]], [[HDAC5|-5]], -7 and [[HDAC9|-9]]; Class IIB [[HDAC6|-6]], and [[HDAC10|-10]] are related to yeast Hda1 gene;\n*Class III, also known as the [[sirtuins]] are related to the Sir2 gene and include SIRT1-7\n*Class IV, which contains only [[HDAC11]] has features of both Class I and II.\n\n=== HDI classification ===\nThe \"classical\" HDIs act exclusively on Class I, II and Class IV HDACs by binding to the zinc-containing catalytic domain of the HDACs.  These classical HDIs can be classified into several groupings named according to the chemical moiety that binds to the zinc ion (except cyclic tetrapeptides which bind to the zinc ion with a thiol group). Some examples in decreasing order of the typical zinc binding affinity:<ref name=Drummond05>{{cite journal | vauthors = Drummond DC, Noble CO, Kirpotin DB, Guo Z, Scott GK, Benz CC | title = Clinical development of histone deacetylase inhibitors as anticancer agents | journal = Annual Review of Pharmacology and Toxicology | volume = 45 | pages = 495\u2013528 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15822187 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.pharmtox.45.120403.095825 }}</ref>\n# [[hydroxamic acid]]s (or hydroxamates), such as [[trichostatin A]],\n# cyclic tetrapeptides (such as trapoxin B), and the [[depsipeptide]]s,\n# [[benzamide]]s,\n# electrophilic [[ketone]]s, and\n# the [[aliphatic]] acid compounds such as [[Sodium phenylbutyrate|phenylbutyrate]] and [[valproic acid]].\n\n\"Second-generation\" HDIs include the hydroxamic acids [[vorinostat]] (SAHA), [[belinostat]] (PXD101), [[LAQ824]], and [[panobinostat]] (LBH589); and the [[benzamide]]s : [[entinostat]] (MS-275), [[tacedinaline]] (CI994), and [[mocetinostat]] (MGCD0103).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beckers T, Burkhardt C, Wieland H, Gimmnich P, Ciossek T, Maier T, Sanders K | title = Distinct pharmacological properties of second generation HDAC inhibitors with the benzamide or hydroxamate head group | journal = International Journal of Cancer | volume = 121 | issue = 5 | pages = 1138\u201348 | date = September 2007 | pmid = 17455259 | doi = 10.1002/ijc.22751 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid15955865\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Acharya MR, Sparreboom A, Venitz J, Figg WD | title = Rational development of histone deacetylase inhibitors as anticancer agents: a review | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 68 | issue = 4 | pages = 917\u201332 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 15955865 | doi = 10.1124/mol.105.014167 }}</ref>\n\nThe sirtuin Class III HDACs are dependent on NAD+ and are, therefore, inhibited by [[nicotinamide]], as well as derivatives of NAD, dihydrocoumarin, naphthopyranone, and 2-hydroxynaphthaldehydes.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Porcu M, Chiarugi A | title = The emerging therapeutic potential of sirtuin-interacting drugs: from cell death to lifespan extension | journal = Trends in Pharmacological Sciences | volume = 26 | issue = 2 | pages = 94\u2013103 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15681027 | doi = 10.1016/j.tips.2004.12.009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Additional functions ===\nHDIs should not be considered to act solely as enzyme inhibitors of HDACs.  A large variety of nonhistone transcription factors and transcriptional co-regulators are known to be modified by acetylation.  HDIs can alter the degree of acetylation nonhistone effector molecules and, therefore, increase or repress the transcription of genes by this mechanism.  Examples include: [[Nuclear receptor coactivator 3|ACTR]], cMyb, [[E2F1]], [[EKLF]], FEN 1, [[GATA transcription factor|GATA]], HNF-4, [[HSP90]], [[Ku70]], [[MKP-1]], [[NF-\u03baB]], [[PCNA]], p53, [[Retinoblastoma protein|RB]], Runx, SF1 Sp3, [[STAT protein|STAT]], [[TFIIE]], [[T-cell|TCF]], [[YY1]], etc.<ref name=Drummond05 /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yang XJ, Seto E | title = HATs and HDACs: from structure, function and regulation to novel strategies for therapy and prevention | journal = Oncogene | volume = 26 | issue = 37 | pages = 5310\u20138 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17694074 | doi = 10.1038/sj.onc.1210599}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Jeong Y, Du R, Zhu X, Yin S, Wang J, Cui H, Cao W, Lowenstein CJ | title = Histone deacetylase isoforms regulate innate immune responses by deacetylating mitogen-activated protein kinase phosphatase-1 | journal = J Leukoc Biol | volume = 95 | issue = 4 | pages = 651\u20139 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24374966 | doi = 10.1189/jlb.1013565}}</ref>\n\n== Uses ==\n\n=== Psychiatry and neurology ===\nHDIs have a long history of use in psychiatry and neurology as mood stabilizers and anti-epileptics.  The prime example of this is [[valproic acid]], marketed as a drug under the trade names ''Depakene'', ''Depakote'', and ''Divalproex''.  In more recent times, HDIs are being studied as a mitigator for [[neurodegenerative diseases]] such as [[Alzheimer's disease]] and [[Huntington's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hahnen E, Hauke J, Tr\u00e4nkle C, Ey\u00fcpoglu IY, Wirth B, Bl\u00fcmcke I | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitors: possible implications for neurodegenerative disorders | journal = Expert Opinion on Investigational Drugs | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 169\u201384 | date = February 2008 | pmid = 18230051 | doi = 10.1517/13543784.17.2.169 }}</ref>\nEnhancement of memory formation is increased in mice given [[vorinostat]], or by genetic knockout of the HDAC2 gene in mice.<ref name=\"pmid19424149\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Guan JS, Haggarty SJ, Giacometti E, Dannenberg JH, Joseph N, Gao J, Nieland TJ, Zhou Y, Wang X, Mazitschek R, Bradner JE, DePinho RA, Jaenisch R, Tsai LH | title = HDAC2 negatively regulates memory formation and synaptic plasticity | journal = Nature | volume = 459 | issue = 7243 | pages = 55\u201360 | date = May 2009 | pmid = 19424149 | pmc = 3498958 | doi = 10.1038/nature07925 | bibcode = 2009Natur.459...55G }}</ref>\nWhile that may have relevance to Alzheimer's disease, it was shown that some cognitive deficits were restored in actual transgenic mice that have a model of Alzheimer's disease (3xTg-AD) by orally administered nicotinamide, a competitive HDI of Class III sirtuins.<ref name=\"pmid18987186\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Green KN, Steffan JS, Martinez-Coria H, Sun X, Schreiber SS, Thompson LM, LaFerla FM | title = Nicotinamide restores cognition in Alzheimer's disease transgenic mice via a mechanism involving sirtuin inhibition and selective reduction of Thr231-phosphotau | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 28 | issue = 45 | pages = 11500\u201310 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18987186 | pmc = 2617713 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3203-08.2008 }}</ref>\n\n==== Pre Clinical Research \u2013 HDI therapy for the treatment of depression ====\nRecent research into the causes of [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] has highlighted some possible [[gene-environment interaction]]s that could explain why after much research, no specific genes or loci which would indicate risk for depression have emerged.<ref name=\"schroeder\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schroeder M, Hillemacher T, Bleich S, Frieling H | title = The epigenetic code in depression: implications for treatment | journal = Clinical Pharmacology and Therapeutics | volume = 91 | issue = 2 | pages = 310\u20134 | date = February 2012 | pmid = 22205200 | doi = 10.1038/clpt.2011.282  }}</ref> Recent studies estimate that even after successive treatments with multiple antidepressants, almost 35% of patients did not achieve remission,<ref name=\"fuchikami\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fuchikami M, Yamamoto S, Morinobu S, Okada S, Yamawaki Y, Yamawaki S | title = The potential use of histone deacetylase inhibitors in the treatment of depression | journal = Progress in Neuro-Psychopharmacology & Biological Psychiatry | volume = 64 | pages = 320\u20134 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 25818247 | doi = 10.1016/j.pnpbp.2015.03.010  }}</ref> suggesting that there could be an epigenetic component to depression that is not being addressed by current pharmacological treatments. Environmental stressors, namely traumatic stress in childhood such as maternal deprivation and early childhood abuse have been studied for their connection to a high risk of depression in adulthood. In animal models, these types of trauma have been shown to have significant effects on [[Histone acetylation and deacetylation|histone acetylation]], particularly at gene [[Locus (genetics)|loci]] which have known connection to behavior and mood regulation.<ref name=\"schroeder\" /><ref name=\"machado\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Machado-Vieira R, Ibrahim L, Zarate CA | title = Histone deacetylases and mood disorders: epigenetic programming in gene-environment interactions | journal = CNS Neuroscience & Therapeutics | volume = 17 | issue = 6 | pages = 699\u2013704 | date = December 2011 | pmid = 20961400 | pmc = 3026916 | doi = 10.1111/j.1755-5949.2010.00203.X }}</ref> Current research has focused on the use of HDI therapy for depression after studies on depressed patients in the middle of a depressive episode found increased expression of HDAC2 and HDAC5 [[mRNA]] compared to controls and patients in remission.<ref name=\"machado\" />\n\n===== Effects on gene expression =====\nVarious HDAC inhibitors (HDI) have been studied for their connection to the regulation of mood and behavior, each having different, specific effects on the regulation of various genes. The most commonly studied genes include [[Brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) and [[Glial cell line-derived neurotrophic factor]] (GDNF) both of which help regulate [[neuron]] growth and health, whose down regulation can be a symptom of depression.<ref name=\"machado\" /> Multiple studies have shown that treatment with an HDI helps to up regulate expression of BDNF: valproic acid (commonly used to treat epilepsy and bipolar disorder)<ref name=\"fuchikami\" /> as well as [[sodium butyrate]]<ref name=\"machado\" /> both increased expression of BDNF in animal models of depression. One study which traced GDNF levels in the [[ventral striatum]] found increased gene expression upon treatment with [[Vorinostat|SAHA]].<ref name=\"fuchikami\" />\n\n===== Effects on depressive behaviors =====\nPre-clinical research on the use of HDAC inhibitors (HDI) for the treatment of depression use rodents to model human depression. The [[tail suspension test]] (TST) and the [[forced swimming test]] (FST) measure the level of defeat in rodents\u2014 usually after treatment with chronic stress\u2014 which mirrors symptoms of human depression. Alongside tests for levels of HDAC mRNA, acetylation and gene expression these behavioral tests are compared to controls to determine whether or not treatment with an HDI has been successful in ameliorating symptoms of depression. Studies which used [[Vorinostat|SAHA]] or [[Entinostat|MS-275]] as their treatment compound found treated animals displayed gene expression profiles similar to those treated with [[Prozac|fluoxetine]], and displayed similar anti-depressant like behavior.<ref name=\"schroeder\" /><ref name =\"fuchikami\" /><ref name=\"machado\" /> Sodium butyrate is commonly used as a candidate for mood disorder treatment: studies using it both alone and in co-treatment with [[Prozac|fluoxetine]] report subjects with increased performance on both TST and FST<ref name=\"fuchikami\" /> in addition to increased expression of BDNF.<ref name=\"machado\" />\n\n=== Cancer treatment ===\n\n=== Inflammatory diseases ===\n[[Trichostatin A]] (TSA) and others are being investigated as anti-inflammatory agents.<ref name=Adcock2007>{{cite journal | vauthors = Adcock IM | title = HDAC inhibitors as anti-inflammatory agents | journal = British Journal of Pharmacology | volume = 150 | issue = 7 | pages = 829\u201331 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17325655 | pmc = 2013887 | doi = 10.1038/sj.bjp.0707166 }}</ref>\n\n=== HIV/AIDS ===\nAfter the successful initial round of ''in vitro'' research in January 2013, the [[Danish Research Council]] awarded the research team led by Dr. Ole S\u00f8gaard from the Danish [[Aarhus University Hospital]] the amount of $2 million to proceed with clinical trials on 15 humans. The goal is for HDAC inhibitors to flush HIV from the reservoirs it builds within the DNA of infected cells, followed by a vaccination to help the immune system to neutralize any replicating virus.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gayomali |first=Chris |title=Breakthrough: Is an HIV cure just a few months away? |newspaper=The Week |publisher=The Week Publications |date=April 29, 2013 |url=http://theweek.com/article/index/243402/breakthrough-is-an-hiv-cure-just-a-few-months-away |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOne study noted the use of [[panobinostat]], [[entinostat]], [[romidepsin]], and [[vorinostat]] specifically for the purpose of reactivating latent HIV in order to diminish the reservoirs. Vorinostat was noted as the least potent of the HDAC inhibitors in this trial.<ref name=\"pmid25393648\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Elliott JH, Wightman F, Solomon A, Ghneim K, Ahlers J, Cameron MJ, Smith MZ, Spelman T, McMahon J, Velayudham P, Brown G, Roney J, Watson J, Prince MH, Hoy JF, Chomont N, Fromentin R, Procopio FA, Zeidan J, Palmer S, Odevall L, Johnstone RW, Martin BP, Sinclair E, Deeks SG, Hazuda DJ, Cameron PU, S\u00e9kaly RP, Lewin SR | name-list-format = vanc  | title = Activation of HIV transcription with short-course vorinostat in HIV-infected patients on suppressive antiretroviral therapy | journal = PLoS Pathogens | volume = 10 | issue = 11 | pages = e1004473 | year = 2014 | pmid = 25393648 | pmc = 4231123 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1004473 }}</ref> Another study found that romidepsin led to a higher and more sustained level of cell-associated HIV RNA reactivation than vorinostat in latently infected T-cells [[in vitro]] and [[ex vivo]].<ref name=\"pmid24722454\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wei DG, Chiang V, Fyne E, Balakrishnan M, Barnes T, Graupe M, Hesselgesser J, Irrinki A, Murry JP, Stepan G, Stray KM, Tsai A, Yu H, Spindler J, Kearney M, Spina CA, McMahon D, Lalezari J, Sloan D, Mellors J, Geleziunas R, Cihlar T | title = Histone deacetylase inhibitor romidepsin induces HIV expression in CD4 T cells from patients on suppressive antiretroviral therapy at concentrations achieved by clinical dosing | journal = PLoS Pathogens | volume = 10 | issue = 4 | pages = e1004071 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24722454 | pmc = 3983056 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1004071 }}</ref>\n\n=== Other diseases ===\n*[[Givinostat]] (ITF2357) is also under investigation for treatment of [[polycythemia vera]] (PV), [[essential thrombocythemia]] (ET) and [[myelofibrosis]] (MF).\n\nHDIs are also being studied as protection of heart muscle in [[acute myocardial infarction]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Granger A, Abdullah I, Huebner F, Stout A, Wang T, Huebner T, Epstein JA, Gruber PJ | title = Histone deacetylase inhibition reduces myocardial ischemia-reperfusion injury in mice | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 22 | issue = 10 | pages = 3549\u201360 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18606865 | pmc = 2537432 | doi = 10.1096/fj.08-108548 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite patent |country=HK |number=1124320 |status=application |title=Novel Sulphonylpyrroles as Inhibitors of Hdac S Novel Sulphonylpyrroles |pubdate=October 22, 2009 |fdate=September 8, 2006 |pridate=September 21, 2005 |inventor=Maier, Thomas; Beckers, Thomas; Hummel, Rolf-Peter; Feth, Martin; M\u00fcller, Matthias; B\u00e4r, Thomas; Volz, J\u00fcrgen}}\n* [http://www.hdacis.com/ HDAC inhibitors base] information about molecules that block HDACs.\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Tambunan US, Wulandari EK | title = Identification of a better Homo sapiens Class II HDAC inhibitor through binding energy calculations and descriptor analysis | journal = BMC Bioinformatics | volume = 11 Suppl 7 | pages = S16 | year = 2010 | pmid = 21106123 | pmc = 2957684 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2105-11-S7-S16 }}\n\n{{HDAC inhibitors}}\n{{Enzyme inhibition}}\n\n[[Category:Histone deacetylase inhibitors| ]]\n[[Category:Antineoplastic drugs]]\n[[Category:Mood stabilizers]]\n", "name_user": "ZMlinaric", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have added a single citation supporting already claimed fact.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histone_deacetylase_inhibitor"}
{"title_page": "Rajendra K. Pachauri", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian academic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| office              = 3rd Chair of the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]]\n| term_start          = 20 April 2002\n| term_end            = 24 February 2015\n| predecessor         = [[Robert Watson (chemist)|Robert Watson]]\n| successor           = [[Hoesung Lee]]\n| name                = Rajendra K. Pachauri\n| image               = Pachauri.jpg\n| caption             = Pachauri in 2002\n| birth_name          = Rajendra Kumar Pachauri\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|df=yes|1940|8|20}}\n| birth_place         = [[Nainital]], [[United Provinces (1937-1950)|United Provinces]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br> (now in [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]])\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|2|13|1940|8|20}}\n| death_place         = [[New Delhi]], [[India]]\n| nationality         = Indian\n| alma_mater          = [[La Martiniere College]], Lucknow; [[North Carolina State University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]] 1972, [[PhD]] 1974)\n| occupation          = Former Chairman, [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]], Former Chairman and Director General, [[The Energy and Resources Institute]] (TERI)\n| spouse              = Saroj Pachauri\n| children            = Ash Pachauri (son) \nRashmi Pachauri Rajan (daughter)\nShonali Pachauri (daughter)\n| parents             = \n| awards              = Padma Vibhushan, Nobel Peace Prize (on behalf of IPCC)\n| signature           = Signature of Rajendra K. Pachauri.jpg\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Legion of Honour| LH]]\n}}\n\n'''Rajendra Kumar Pachauri''' (20 August 1940 \u2013 13 February 2020<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/14/science/rajendra-pachauri-dead.html</ref>) was the chairman of the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC), and was succeeded by [[Hoesung Lee]].  He held the post from 2002 until his resignation in February 2015.<ref name='bbc'>{{cite news | first = Vindhi | last = Doshi | date = 22 Apr 2016 | title = Rajendra Pachauri to face Delhi court on sexual harassment charges | publisher = BBC | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/22/rajendra-pachauri-court-delhi-sexual-assault-charges | accessdate = 25 Jan 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170322064842/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/22/rajendra-pachauri-court-delhi-sexual-assault-charges | archivedate = 22 March 2017}}</ref>  The IPCC was awarded the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] during his tenure.<ref name=\"AP_2007-12-10_msn\"/><ref name=\"Rajendra_2007-12-10_nobel\"/> He was the Chairman and Director General of [[The Energy and Resources Institute]] (TERI). The Governing Council of TERI appointed Ashok Chawla as its new chairman in February 2016 who had to eventually step down over corruption charges.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/pachauri-proceeds-on-leave-ashok-chawla-is-chairman-of-teri/article8228661.ece|title=Pachauri proceeds on leave, Ashok Chawla is chairman of TERI|date=2016-02-12|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Ajay Mathur, a technocrat in the [[Bureau of Energy Efficiency]], was appointed as the Director General of TERI by the Governing Council in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/rk-pachauri-asked-to-step-down-ajay-mathur-is-new-teri-chief/|title=Pachauri asked to step down, Ajay Mathur named new TERI chief|date=2015-07-24|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nPachauri was born in [[Nainital]], India. He was educated at [[La Martiniere Lucknow|La Martiniere College]] in [[Lucknow]]<ref name=\"2009-06-25_iloveindia\"/> and at the [[Indian Railways Institute of Mechanical and Electrical Engineering]] in [[Jamalpur, Bihar]]. He belonged to the [[Special Class Railway Apprentice]]s, 1958 Batch, an elite scheme which heralded the beginning of mechanical engineering education in India.<ref>{{cite news | first = Tarannum | last = Manjul | title = At DLW, Pachy still brings a smile on employees' faces | date = 14 October 2007 | url = http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/at-dlw-pachy-still-brings-a-smile-on-employees-faces/228140/ | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130122175150/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/at-dlw-pachy-still-brings-a-smile-on-employees-faces/228140/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = 22 January 2013 | work = [[Indian Express]] | accessdate = 14 January 2012 }}</ref> He began his career with the [[Indian Railways]] at the [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] in [[Varanasi]]. He was admitted to [[North Carolina State University]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], United States, where he obtained an [[Master of Science|MS]] in [[Industrial Engineering]] in 1972, and a [[PhD]] with co-majors in Industrial Engineering and [[Economics]] in 1974.<ref name=\"ncsu\"/> His doctoral thesis was titled ''A dynamic model for forecasting of electrical ebhj bhvbiggemand in a specific region located in [[North Carolina|North]] and [[South Carolina]]''.<ref name=OCLC>{{cite book |author=Pachauri, Rajendra K. | title=A dynamic model for forecasting of electrical energy demand in a specific region located in North and South Carolina |year=1974 |oclc=19806155 }}</ref> He was a strict vegetarian, largely because of \"[[environmental vegetarianism|the environmental and climate change implications]].\"<ref name=\"Pachauri_2014-04-18_Chomping_Climate_Change\"/>\n\n==Career==\nHe served as Assistant Professor (August 1974 \u2013 May 1975) and Visiting Faculty Member (Summer 1976 and 1977) in the Department of Economics and Business at NC State. He was a Visiting Professor of Resource Economics at the College of Mineral and Energy Resources, [[West Virginia University]]. On his return to India, he joined the [[Administrative Staff College of India]], Hyderabad, as Member Senior Faculty (June 1975 \u2013 June 1979) and went on to become Director, Consulting and Applied Research Division (July 1979 \u2013 March 1981). He joined [[The Energy and Resources Institute]] (TERI) as Director in 1982.<ref name=\"climatescience\"/> He was also a Senior Visiting Fellow at the Resource Systems Institute (1982), and Visiting Research Fellow at the World Bank, Washington DC (1990). On 20 April 2002, Pachauri was elected Chairman of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, a United Nations panel established by the [[World Meteorological Organization]] (WMO) and [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP) to assess information relevant for understanding climate change.<ref name=\"2002-04-20_ipcc\"/>\n\nPachauri was on the Board of Governors, Shriram Scientific and Industrial Research Foundation (September 1987); the Executive Committee of the [[India International Centre]], New Delhi (1985 onwards); the Governing Council of the [[India Habitat Centre]], New Delhi (October 1987 onwards); and the Court of Governors, Administrative Staff College of India (1979\u201381) and advises such companies as [[Pegasus Capital Advisors]], the [[Chicago Climate Exchange]], [[Toyota]], [[Deutsche Bank]] and [[National Thermal Power Corporation|NTPC]].<ref name=\"2010-02-01_BusinessWeek\"/> He has served as member of many societies and commissions. He has been the Member of Board of the International Solar Energy Society (1991\u20131997), World Resources Institute Council (1992), while Chairman of the World Energy Council (1993\u20131995), President and then Chairman of the International Association for Energy Economics (1988\u20131990), and the President of the Asian Energy Institute (Since 1992).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lifestyle.iloveindia.com/lounge/r-k-pachauri-1032.html |title=R.K. Pachauri Biography \u2013 R.K. Pachauri Profile, Rajendra Kumar Pachauri Timeline |publisher=Lifestyle.iloveindia.com |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> He was a part-time advisor to the United Nations Development Programme (1994\u20141999) in the fields of Energy and Sustainable Management of Natural Resources.<ref name=\"climatescience1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.climatescience.gov/Library/bios/pachauri.htm |title=Biography: Dr. R.K. Pachauri |publisher=Climatescience.gov |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118170119/http://www.climatescience.gov/Library/bios/pachauri.htm |archivedate=18 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In July 2001, Dr R K Pachauri was appointed Member, Economic Advisory Council to the Prime Minister of India.<ref name=\"climatescience1\"/>\n\n===Work with the IPCC===\nOn 20 April 2002, Pachauri was elected Chairman of the United Nations established Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change and during his tenure the IPCC received the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref name=\"2002-04-20_ipcc\"/>\n\nPachauri was vocal on the issue of [[climate change]] and said, \"What is happening, and what is likely to happen, convinces me that the world must be really ambitious and very determined at moving toward a 350 target.\"<ref name=\"Hood_2009-08-25_AFP\"/> 350 refers to the level in parts per million of [[Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere|carbon dioxide in the atmosphere]] that some climate scientists such as NASA's [[James Hansen]] agree to be a [[Planetary boundaries#The nine boundaries|safe upper limit]] to avoid a [[Tipping point (climatology)|climate tipping point]].<ref name=\"Whitesides_2009-12-28_Wired\"/> His career with IPCC came to an abrupt end after the sexual harassment charges against him surfaced in Indian courts.\n\n===2007 Nobel Peace Prize for IPCC===\n[[Image:Nobel Peace Prize winners Gore & Pachauri in Grand Hotel, Norway 2.jpg|thumb|right|Pachauri and [[Al Gore]] on the balcony of the [[Grand Hotel (Oslo)|Grand Hotel, Oslo]].]]\n\nThe IPCC shared the 2007 [[Nobel Peace Prize]] with former US Vice-President [[Al Gore]], who had earlier criticised Pachauri when he was first elected in 2002.<ref name=\"2007-10-12_reuters\"/> In its press release,<ref name=\"2007-10-12_nobelprize\"/> the Nobel Prize Committee said:\n\n:...the Nobel Peace Prize for 2007 is to be shared, in two equal parts, between the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) and Albert Arnold (Al) Gore Jr. for their efforts to build up and disseminate greater knowledge about man-made climate change, and to lay the foundations for the measures that are needed to counteract such change.\"<ref name=\"2007-10-12_nobelprize\"/>\n\nOn 11 December 2007, Pachauri (representing the recipient IPCC) and co-recipient Al Gore delivered their acceptance speeches at an awards ceremony in [[Oslo, Norway]], on a day when delegates to a United Nations climate conference were meeting in [[Bali, Indonesia]].<ref name=\"Jordan_2007-12-11_washingtonpost\"/> Pachauri referenced his belief that the Hindu philosophy of \"'[[Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam]]', which means 'the whole universe is one family,'\" must dominate global efforts to protect the global commons.\"<ref name=DemNow/> Returning to this theme throughout his speech, he quoted president of the [[Maldives]] in 1987 ([[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]]):\n\n:\"...a mean sea level rise of two meters would suffice to virtually submerge the entire country of 1,190 small islands, most of which barely rise two meters above sea level. That would be the death of a nation.\"<ref name=DemNow/>\n\nPachauri repeatedly emphasised his concerns regarding the implications of climate change for the world's poorest nations, referring to studies that:\n\n:\"...have raised the threat of dramatic population migration, conflict, and war over water and other resources, as well as a realignment of power among nations. Some also highlight the possibility of rising tensions between rich and poor nations, health problems caused particularly by water shortages and crop failures...\n\n===Commitment to other organisations===\nRajendra K. Pachauri was a member of the [[Jacques Chirac Foundation for Sustainable Development and Cultural Dialogue|Fondation Chirac]]'s honour committee,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fondationchirac.eu/en/foundation/honour-committee/|title=Honor Committee|author=|date=|website=fondationchirac.eu|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> since its launch in 2008 by former French president [[Jacques Chirac]] to promote world peace.\n\n==Lighting a Billion Lives Initiative==\nPachauri conceptualised and launched the global 'Lighting a Billion Live's (LaBL) initiative in 2008, to facilitate clean energy access to the energy poor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/catalyst/2009/12/24/stories/2009122450120400.htm |title=Business Line : Features / BrandLine News |publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718100640/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/catalyst/2009/12/24/stories/2009122450120400.htm |archivedate=18 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Lighting a Billion Lives - About us|url = http://labl.teriin.org/about.php|website = labl.teriin.org|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref> The initiative has taken solar energy to remote places such as [[Sundarbans]], West Bengal, [[Thar Desert]], Rajasthan, and in the state of [[Bihar]].  Being an early advocate for integration of access to clean cooking and lighting solution, the initiative has successfully deployed several thousands of Integrated Domestic Energy Systems (IDES) in rural and remote areas. It has set several benchmarks and has emphasized on access to a menu of clean energy options for the poor at last mile locations. LaBL has also been a platform for several technology manufacturers to start-up with business in the clean energy space. The initiative has its footfalls in 13 plus countries and 23 plus states of India.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lighting a Billion Lives - Evolution|url = http://labl.teriin.org/evolution.php|website = labl.teriin.org|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{Criticism section|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Allegations of conflict of interest and financial anomalies===\n[[Christopher Booker]] and [[Richard North (blogger)|Richard North]] wrote an article for the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' in January 2010 alleging potential conflicts of interest related to Pachauri's membership of the board of [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation|ONGC]]<ref name=\"Singh_2010-01-10_indiatoday\"/> and to research grants for [[The Energy and Resources Institute|TERI]], a non-profit institution of which Pachauri was director general.<ref name=\"Mendick_2010-01-16_telegraph\"/> They further alleged that financial anomalies existed at TERI Europe.<ref name=\"Brooker_2010-01-17_telegraph\"/> Pachauri denied all allegations.<ref name=\"Pachauri_2010-01-04_guardian\"/><ref name=\"2009-12-24_thehindu\"/>\n\nIn response to the allegations, the audit firm [[KPMG]] carried out a review at TERI's request.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/interactive/2010/aug/26/kpmg-review-pachauri-accounts | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=KPMG review of personal financial records of Dr Rajendra Pachauri | date=26 August 2010}}</ref> The review stated: \"No evidence was found that indicated personal financial benefits accruing to Dr Pachauri from his various advisory roles that would have led to a conflict of interest\".  The report explains its objectives and methodology and states that \"Work done by us was as considered necessary at that point in time\" and that it is based on the information provided by TERI, Pachauri and Pachauri's tax counsel. In a caveat the review explains that its scope was \"significantly different from an audit and cannot be relied on to provide the same level of assurance as an audit\".<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> [[KPMG]] examined payments made by private sector companies and found that payments amounting to $326,399 were made to TERI itself, not to Pachauri.<ref name=\"Pachauri cleared Guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2010/aug/26/rajendra-pachauri-cleared-financial-dealings |title=Rajendra Pachauri cleared of financial misdealings &#124; Environment |author=George Monbiot  |authorlink=George Monbiot |author2=James Randerson  |date=26 August 2010 |newspaper= The Guardian |accessdate=27 August 2010 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"FT 2010-03-28\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/44a0a92c-3a8e-11df-b6d5-00144feabdc0.html |title=FT.com / In depth \u2013 Climate chief cleared over payments |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |accessdate=29 March 2010}}</ref> He had received only his annual salary from TERI, amounting to \u00a345,000 a year, plus a maximum of about \u00a32,174 from outside earnings. He received no payment for chairing the IPCC.<ref name=\"Monbiot\" />\n\nOn 21 August 2010, the ''Daily Telegraph'' issued an apology, saying that it had \"not intended to suggest that Dr Pachauri was corrupt or abusing his position as head of the IPCC and we accept KPMG found Dr Pachauri had not made \"millions of dollars\" in recent years.\" It stated: \"We apologise to Dr Pachauri for any embarrassment caused.\"<ref name=\"Deccan- T apologises\">{{cite news |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/90407/daily-telegraph-apologises-pachauri-over.html |title=Daily Telegraph apologises to Pachauri over damning article |date=20 August 2010 |newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> The Guardian reported that the Telegraph paid legal costs of over \u00a3100,000.<ref name=\"Monbiot\">{{cite news|last=Monbiot|first=George|title=Rajendra Pachauri innocent of financial misdealings but smears will continue|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/georgemonbiot/2010/aug/26/rajendra-pachauri-financial-relationships|date=26 August 2010|accessdate=26 August 2010 | location=London | work=The Guardian}}</ref> Pachauri welcomed the ''Telegraph's'' apology, saying that he was \"glad that they have finally acknowledged the truth\", and attributed the false allegations to \"another attempt by the [[climate sceptics]] to discredit the IPCC. They now want to go after me and hope that it would serve their purpose.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Daily Telegraph apologises to Pachauri|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Daily-Telegraph-apologises-to-Pachauri-over-an-article-alleging-corruption/Article1-589993.aspx|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103020626/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Daily-Telegraph-apologises-to-Pachauri-over-an-article-alleging-corruption/Article1-589993.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 January 2013|date=21 August 2010|accessdate=26 August 2010|agency=Press Trust of India|work=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\n[[George Monbiot]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated his view that despite Pachauri being cleared by KPMG of conflict of interest and financial wrongdoing, false claims had been repeated about him by Richard North, the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Australian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monbiot|first=George|title=Press continue to hound Rajendra Pachauri despite his innocence|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/georgemonbiot/2010/sep/01/rajendra-pachauri-ipcc|date=1 September 2010 | accessdate=2 September 2010 | location=London | work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment case===\n{{POV section|date=August 2018}}\nOn 18 February 2015, Delhi police filed a First Information Report (FIR) against Pachauri on allegations of sexual harassment, stalking and criminal intimidation.<ref>[https://archive.today/20150720101716/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-05-23/news/62544230_1_rk-pachauri-internal-complaints-committee-sexual-harassment ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/delhi-police-fir-against-r-k-pachauri-on-charges-of-sexual-harassment/|title=Delhi Police FIR against R K Pachauri on charges of sexual harassment|author=|date=20 February 2015|website=indianexpress.com|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> On March 21, the Delhi High Court granted him anticipatory bail.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2015/03/rajendra-pachauri-granted-anticipatory-bail-in-sexual-harassment-case/|title=Rajendra Pachauri granted Anticipatory Bail in Sexual Harassment Case|date=21 March 2015|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|agency=ANI|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> While in May 2015, Pachauri was found guilty of sexual harassment by an internal complaints committee (ICC) of TERI,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-09-22/news/66792221_1_rk-pachauri-teri-and-pachauri-delhi-hc-issues|title=Delhi HC issues notices to government, TERI, RK Pachauri in sexual harassment case|date=22 September 2015|newspaper=Economic Times|agency=ET Bureau|language=English|quote=...director general RK Pachauri despite his being found guilty of sexual harassment, stalking and criminal intimidation by the organisation's internal complaints committee (ICC).|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> the findings of the ICC have been challenged before the Industrial Tribunal on the grounds of violation of the [[principles of natural justice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/industrial-tribunal-stays-teris-report-against-rajendra-pachauri-till-july-15/articleshow/47476578.cms|title=Industrial Tribunal stays TERI's report against Rajendra Pachauri till July 15 - The Economic Times|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> An article in an Indian magazine [[The Caravan]] detailed the exploits of RK Pachauri during his tenure at TERI.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hostile Climate:R.K.Pachauri's reign at TERI|url=http://www.caravanmagazine.in/reportage/hostile-climate-rk-pachauri-reign-teri}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement, Pachauri said that the contents of the charge sheet are \u201callegations\u201d levelled by the complainant and nothing has been \u201csubstantiated\u201d after a year-long investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abplive.in/india-news/pachauri-claims-done-no-wrong-after-court-takes-cognizance-of-charge-sheet-343105|title=Pachauri claims done no wrong after court takes cognizance of charge sheet|date=17 May 2016|publisher=ABP Live}}</ref>  Pachauri has maintained: \u201cFrom my perspective this was nothing but a very cordial and mutual relationship. There was a light and friendly tone to our correspondence, but at no stage did I ever hint at having a physical relationship nor did I in any way engage in sexual harassment\u201d.<ref name=\"Vidal\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/mar/26/rajendra-pachauri-hits-back-harassed-female-colleague-claims|title=Rajendra Pachauri speaks out over sexual harassment claims|last=Vidal|first=John|date=2016-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Pachauri was granted regular bail from the trial court in July 2016. The court observed \"The investigation of the case is complete. Charge sheet has already been filed. He was never arrested during the investigation in the instant case which goes on to show that his custody is not required for the purpose of investigation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/ex-teri-chief-rk-pachauri-granted-bail-allowed-to-travel-abroad-2907014/|title=Ex-TERI chief RK Pachauri granted bail, allowed to travel abroad|date=2016-07-11|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n*In January 2001, India's Government awarded him the [[Padma Bhushan]].<ref name=\"mha_nic_2001\"/><ref name=\"climatescience\"/>\n*[[NDTV Indian of the Year|NDTV Global Indian of the Year]] for the year 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lifestyle.iloveindia.com/lounge/ndtv-indian-of-the-year-540.html |title=Lifestyle Sitemap |publisher=Lifestyle.iloveindia.com |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113210324/http://lifestyle.iloveindia.com/lounge/ndtv-indian-of-the-year-540.html |archivedate=13 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Nature]] News maker of the Year 2007. The magazine lauded Pachauri in an article as an organisation builder \"Rajendra Pachauri's great strength is in building and organizing institutions in the fields he understands best \u2013 engineering and economics as they apply to issues of development\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/nature-names-pachauri-newsmaker-of-the-year/54627-11.html?from=search |title=Nature names Pachauri Newsmaker of the Year \u2013 Tech News \u2013 IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n*On 14 July 2008, Pachauri received the title [[UNIDO]] [[Goodwill ambassador|Goodwill Ambassador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unido.org/index.php?id=5750 |title=Pachauri |publisher=unido.org |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n*In January 2008, he was awarded the second-highest civilian award in India, the [[Padma Vibhushan]].<ref name=\"mha_nic_2008\"/>\n*In November 2009, Pachauri received the '[[Order of the Rising Sun]] \u2013 Gold and Silver Star' in recognition of his contribution to the enhancement of Japan's policy towards climate change. He was bestowed with the decoration by Emperor [[Akihito]].<ref name=\"Krishnamurthy_2009-11-03_newkerala\"/>\n*In November 2009, Pachauri was rated fifth in the list of \"Top 100 Global thinkers\" by [[Foreign Policy]] magazine, for \"ending the debate over whether climate change matters.\"<ref name=\"2009-11-30_foreignpolicy\"/>\n*In February 2010, the President of Finland conferred the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]] to Pachauri in recognition of his work in promoting international co-operation on climate change and sustainable development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teriin.org/index.php?option=com_pressrelease&task=details&sid=176 |title=Dr R K Pachauri conferred with The Order of the White Rose of Finland |publisher=Teriin.org |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n*The French government has awarded him the 'Officer of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur|Legion of Honour]]'.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/article36756.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Mohammed | last=Iqbal | title=Jaipur Professor gets highest French honour | date=21 October 2009}}</ref>\n*[[HEC Paris]] appointed Pachauri Professor ''Honoris Causa'' in October 2009.<ref name=\"Ward_2009-06-10_MBACHANNEL\"/>\n*[[University of Reims Champagne-Ardenne]] appointed Pachauri Professor ''Honoris Causa'' in September 2012.<ref>[http://www.univ-reims.fr/vie-des-campus/actualites,10453,19060.html?&args=Y29tcF9pZD04NiZhY3Rpb249ZGV0YWlsJmlkPTY2OCZ8 accessed 1 October 2012]</ref>\n*In July 2013, the [[Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio di Mirandola]] conferred Pachauri with the Pico della Mirandola Prize\n\n==Other interests==\nOther than his academic publications, Pachauri also wrote poetry and fiction. He is the author of ''Return to Almora'',<ref name=\"Pachauri_2010_RupaAndCo\"/> a [[romance novel]] published in 2010. The novel is in the form of the reminiscences of a retired bureaucrat, once an engineering student, about his spiritual and sexual past.<ref name=\"Joseph_2010-01-23_TimesofIndia\"/><ref name=\"Mendick_2010-01-30_Telegraph\"/> He co-wrote ''Moods and Musings'',<ref name=\"Pachauri_2003_WritersWorkshop\"/> a collection of poems, with his daughter Rashmi Pachauri-Rajan.<ref name=\"Saha_2007-10-13_telegraphindia\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[TERI University]]\n* [[The Energy and Resources Institute]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"2002-04-20_ipcc\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/press/media-flash-20april2002.pdf\n |title       = Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Elects Dr. Rajendra K. Pachauri as its Chairman\n |accessdate  = 5 December 2008\n |date        = 20 April 2002\n |publisher   = [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100113183144/http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/press/media-flash-20april2002.pdf\n |archivedate = 13 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2007-10-12_reuters\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-29968820071012\n |title       = Pachauri buries Gore feud after Nobel\n |work   = Reuters\n |date        = 12 October 2007\n |accessdate  = 5 February 2010\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090216212256/http://in.reuters.com/article/topNews/idINIndia-29968820071012\n |archivedate = 16 February 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2007-10-12_nobelprize\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/2007/press.html\n |title       = The Nobel Peace Prize for 2007 \u2013 press release\n |work        = [[nobelprize.org]]\n |publisher   = [[The Norwegian Nobel Committee]]\n |date        = 12 October 2007\n |accessdate  = 5 February 2010\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100109120132/http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/2007/press.html\n |archivedate = 9 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2009-06-25_iloveindia\">{{cite web|url=http://lifestyle.iloveindia.com/lounge/r-k-pachauri-1032.html |title=R. K. Pachauri biography on I love India website |publisher=Lifestyle.iloveindia.com |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"2009-11-30_foreignpolicy\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2009/11/30/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=full |title=The FP Top 100 Global Thinkers \u2013 5. Rajendra Pachauri |publisher=Foreignpolicy.com |accessdate=3 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514125801/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2009/11/30/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=full |archivedate=14 May 2011 